"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535186","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-07-14","<p>The provisions restricting the use of lifetime tenancies are intended to ensure we get the best use out of our social housing stock - ensuring that social housing is focussed on those who need it the most for as long as they need it. This is essential with 1.24 million households on council waiting lists. The changes will apply to new tenants, but will not apply to existing lifetime tenants who remain in their own home.</p><p>If tenants are required to move home by their landlord, for example to allow demolition and regeneration work to take place, they will be granted a tenancy with no less security in their new home.</p><p>Where existing lifetime tenants seek to transfer, local authorities will retain a discretion – in limited circumstances – to offer the tenant a further lifetime tenancy in their new home. We will set out the circumstances in which local authorities may exercise this discretion in regulations. We expect these will include where tenants downsize into a smaller home, move for work or to escape violence.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2016-07-14T08:41:25.283Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535186/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535186/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535186/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-07-11","Tenancy Agreements","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, which tenants will be exempt from the Government's proposed phasing out of lifetime tenancies.","false","Biography information for Dr Roberta Blackman-Woods","City of Durham","Dr Roberta Blackman-Woods","42408"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535187","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-07-14","<p>I replied to the hon. Member on 11 July 2016.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2016-07-14T08:42:20.397Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535187/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535187/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535187/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-07-11","Members: Correspondence","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, when he plans to respond to the letter to his Department from the hon. Member for Wolverhampton South West of 5 May 2016 on neighbourhood plans, reference ZA3476.","false","Biography information for Rob Marris","Wolverhampton South West","Rob Marris","42281"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535188","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-07-19","<p>The homelessness legislation (part 7 Housing Act 1996) provides a strong safety net for all those who are vulnerable and homeless through no fault of their own. Homelessness is defined at section 175 of the Act. Broadly speaking somebody is statutorily homeless if they do not have accommodation that they have a legal right to occupy, which is accessible and physically available to them (and their household) and which it would be reasonable for them to continue to live in. It would not be reasonable for someone to continue to live in their home, for example, if that was likely to lead to violence against them (or a member of their family).</p><p>We have protected homelessness prevention funding for local authorities, totalling £315 million by 2020. In doing so, we expect local authorities to meet their statutory duty to provide advice and assistance to all those that approach them for help. Since 2010, this funding has allowed local authorities to prevent more than a million households from becoming homeless. We are determined to ensure that we prevent more people from becoming homeless in the first place so we are working with local authorities, homelessness charities and across departments to consider options to prevent more people from becoming homeless.</p><p>We have also increased central funding to tackle homelessness to £139 million over the next four years, which will include targeted funding for rough sleeping. This includes a new £10 million fund to support and scale-up initiatives to prevent and reduce rough sleeping, and a £10 million Social Impact Bond to support the most entrenched rough sleepers off the streets.</p><p> </p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2016-07-19T16:29:29.857Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535188/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535188/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535188/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-07-11","Sleeping Rough","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what assessment he has made of the effectiveness of the definition of statutory homelessness in preventing rough sleeping.","false","Biography information for Michael Dugher","Barnsley East","Michael Dugher","42322"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535189","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-07-19","<p>The Department does not hold information about loans made from public collections. The national museums and galleries have responsibility for their specific loan arrangements and information about their loans is not held centrally.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>All Government funded museums and galleries are encouraged to loan works from their collections to institutions across the UK.Sponsored National Museums actively support and partner regional museums, which includes touring and large scale loans. In 2014/15 the national museums and galleries loaned items to 1,629 venues, including regional museums and historic houses.</p><p> </p><p>A new tax relief for museums and galleries will be introduced from 1 April 2017 to encourage them to develop creative new exhibitions and display their collections across the country. The relief will be available on qualifying costs for temporary and touring exhibitions.</p><p> </p><p>An independent report by Lord Heseltine, published in June, makes recommendations to further develop the Tees Valley area. The report called Tees Valley: Opportunity Unlimited has strong arts and cultural content and says the area hosts public art of national significance. The report also highlights the strengths of museums and galleries in the region, which include the Middlesbrough Institute of Modern Art (MiMA), the MOD funded Museum of the Royal Navy’s HMS Trincomalee in Hartlepool, the &quot;Head of Steam&quot; Railway Museum in Darlington and the Science Museum Group’s Locomotion branch at Shildon near Darlington.</p><p> </p><p>MiMa is a Tate Plus partner and has strong links with Tate Modern. It receives funding from Arts Council England as a Visual Arts Gallery. The Government is also funding £500k towards the development of a new Captain Cook exhibition resource at the Captain Cook Birthplace Museum in Middlesbrough.</p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock",,"2016-07-19T08:05:59.423Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535189/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535189/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535189/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-07-11","Art Works: Redcar and Cleveland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, how many works of art from public collections were loaned to institutions in Redcar and Cleveland in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Anna Turley","Redcar","Anna Turley","42348"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535190","Department for Education","false","2016-07-19","<p>We want all pupils to be healthy and active. We have ring-fenced over £450 million to improve PE and sport in primary schools (2013/14 - 2015/16), and committed to doubling the primary PE and sport premium to £320 million a year from September 2017 using revenue from the soft drinks industry levy. Schools have the freedom to decide how to use the funding based on the needs of their pupils, and can choose to target funding on the least active and children from poorer socio-economic backgrounds. Schools are accountable for their spending through Ofsted inspections and are required to report plans and impact online.</p><p>We have evaluated the impact and schools’ use of the premium through the independent research company, NatCen. Evidence indicates the funding is having a positive impact and schools reported almost universally that the PE and sport premium had had a positive impact on physical fitness (99%), healthy lifestyles (99%), skills (98%) and behaviour of pupils (96%).[1].</p><p>We are currently exploring options for future evaluation once the premium is doubled. Further details will be announced in due course.</p><p> </p><p>[1] Evidence from the 2015 report, based on findings of a two year study between 2013 – 2015: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/pe-and-sport-premium-an-investigation-in-primary-schools" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/pe-and-sport-premium-an-investigation-in-primary-schools</a></p><p> </p>","Crewe and Nantwich","Edward Timpson","42422","2016-07-19T15:45:30.313Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535190/answer","Biography information for Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535190/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535190/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-07-11","Primary Education: Sports","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, if her Department will take steps to ensure that new investment in the Primary PE and Sport Premium directly benefits (a) the least active children and (b) children from poorer socio-economic backgrounds.","false","Biography information for Sir David Amess","Southend West","Sir David Amess","42421"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535191","Department for Education","false","2016-07-19","<p>We want all pupils to be healthy and active. We have ring-fenced over £450 million to improve PE and sport in primary schools (2013/14 - 2015/16), and committed to doubling the primary PE and sport premium to £320 million a year from September 2017 using revenue from the soft drinks industry levy. Schools have the freedom to decide how to use the funding based on the needs of their pupils, and can choose to target funding on the least active and children from poorer socio-economic backgrounds. Schools are accountable for their spending through Ofsted inspections and are required to report plans and impact online.</p><p>We have evaluated the impact and schools’ use of the premium through the independent research company, NatCen. Evidence indicates the funding is having a positive impact and schools reported almost universally that the PE and sport premium had had a positive impact on physical fitness (99%), healthy lifestyles (99%), skills (98%) and behaviour of pupils (96%).[1].</p><p>We are currently exploring options for future evaluation once the premium is doubled. Further details will be announced in due course.</p><p> </p><p>[1] Evidence from the 2015 report, based on findings of a two year study between 2013 – 2015: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/pe-and-sport-premium-an-investigation-in-primary-schools" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/pe-and-sport-premium-an-investigation-in-primary-schools</a></p><p> </p>","Crewe and Nantwich","Edward Timpson","42421","2016-07-19T15:45:30.377Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535191/answer","Biography information for Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535191/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535191/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-07-11","Primary Education: Sports","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what steps her Department is taking to monitor the effect on children's fitness and activity levels of the Primary PE and Sport Premium.","false","Biography information for Sir David Amess","Southend West","Sir David Amess","42422"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535192","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-07-18","<p>We want to ensure that all children, regardless of background, ability or where they live, are able to engage in sport and physical activity in a way that interests and benefits them. Through the Government's sports strategy Sporting Future, published in December 2015, Sport England will now invest in sporting provision for children aged five and over - previously the starting age was 14 years old.</p><p> </p><p>In addition, Sport England's new strategy, Towards an Active Nation, published in May 2016, sets out their plans to make a major new investment of £40 million into projects which offer new opportunities for families with children to get active and play sport together. Sport England will continue to work with organisations across the sport sector as it implements its strategy.</p>","Chatham and Aylesford","Tracey Crouch",,"2016-07-18T14:28:11.177Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535192/answer","Biography information for Tracey Crouch","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535192/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535192/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-07-11","Health: Children","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, if Sport England will take steps to ensure that children's fitness and activity levels do not decline from their term-time levels in the summer holidays.","false","Biography information for Sir David Amess","Southend West","Sir David Amess","42423"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535193","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-07-14","A new Europe unit is being set up in Whitehall, bringing together officials and policy expertise from across government. This unit will be led by and staffed by the best and brightest from across the civil service, including DCMS.<p> </p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2016-07-14T09:20:30.917Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535193/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535193/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535193/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-07-11","Department for Culture, Media and Sport: Cabinet Office EU Unit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, how many full-time equivalent staff of his Department (a) have moved and (b) are planned to move into the EU Unit.","false","Biography information for Chi Onwurah","Newcastle upon Tyne Central","Chi Onwurah","42454"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535194","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-07-19","<p>As set out in the 2015 Strategic Defence and Security Review, we are taking steps to manage the defence nuclear enterprise and ensure the Successor submarines are delivered to time and budget. As part of this, we have established a new Director-General Nuclear to act as single and accountable focal point within the Ministry of Defence for all aspects of the defence nuclear enterprise. We are also establishing a new submarine delivery body for the procurement and in-service support of all nuclear submarines, including the Successor submarines. We have deliberately moved away from a traditional single 'Main Gate' approach, to a staged investment approach with multiple control points. This will enable us to better regulate and control programme funding and delivery.</p><p>The rollout of the Successor submarines supports the programme to maintain a Continuous at Sea Deterrent.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin","42452","2016-07-19T15:08:19.667Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535194/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535194/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535194/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-07-11","Trident","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what steps his Department has taken to ensure that the actual cost of replacing Trident does not exceed the current estimated cost.","false","Biography information for Andrew Rosindell","Romford","Andrew Rosindell","42451"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535195","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-07-19","<p>As set out in the 2015 Strategic Defence and Security Review, we are taking steps to manage the defence nuclear enterprise and ensure the Successor submarines are delivered to time and budget. As part of this, we have established a new Director-General Nuclear to act as single and accountable focal point within the Ministry of Defence for all aspects of the defence nuclear enterprise. We are also establishing a new submarine delivery body for the procurement and in-service support of all nuclear submarines, including the Successor submarines. We have deliberately moved away from a traditional single 'Main Gate' approach, to a staged investment approach with multiple control points. This will enable us to better regulate and control programme funding and delivery.</p><p>The rollout of the Successor submarines supports the programme to maintain a Continuous at Sea Deterrent.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin","42451","2016-07-19T15:08:19.743Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535195/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535195/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535195/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-07-11","Trident Submarines","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what steps his Department is taking to ensure that the rollout of the new submarines for the replacement Trident programme does not disrupt the Government's commitment to having a constant at-sea deterrent.","false","Biography information for Andrew Rosindell","Romford","Andrew Rosindell","42452"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535196","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-07-14","<p>Data on Service Family Accommodation (SFA) houses that did not meet the decent homes standard in each of the last five years is not held as the Ministry of Defence (MOD) only started assessing houses against this standard in April 2016.</p><p>As of 12 July 91.6% of SFA houses met or exceeded the decent homes standard.</p><p>The information on the historical condition of SFA demonstrated a steady increase in condition against the 'Standard for Condition' metrics. Under this system 96% of SFA was at the top two standards for condition which broadly equated to the decent homes standard.</p><p>Any family currently living in a property that does not meet the decent homes standard has the option to move, but will not be forced to move. The MOD does not allocate properties below the decent homes standard to families.</p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster",,"2016-07-14T15:33:31.47Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535196/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535196/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535196/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-07-11","Armed Forces: Housing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, how many service family accommodation homes have not met the Decent Homes standard in each of the last five years,","false","Biography information for Tim Farron","Westmorland and Lonsdale","Tim Farron","42389"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535197","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-07-15","<p>As part of the Global Coalition, the RAF has conducted airstrikes and surveillance in support of Syrian Democratic Forces offensives in the east of Syria and more recently around Manbij.</p>","Sevenoaks","Michael Fallon",,"2016-07-15T13:32:28.957Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535197/answer","Biography information for Sir Michael Fallon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535197/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535197/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-07-11","Syria: Military Intervention","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what assistance his Department has provided to Kurdish forces in Syria in their fight against Daesh in the last 12 months.","false","Biography information for Natalie McGarry","Glasgow East","Natalie McGarry","42379"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535198","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-07-14","<p>The following number of Brimstone missiles have been released by RAF aircraft engaged on Operation SHADER up to and including 11 Jul 2016 since the start of operations:</p><p> </p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Munition</p></td><td><p>Iraq</p></td><td><p>Syria</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Brimstone</p></td><td><p>175</p></td><td><p>19</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p> </p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2016-07-14T15:34:21.047Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535198/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535198/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535198/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-07-11","Middle East: Military Intervention","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, how many Brimstone missiles have been fired by RAF warplanes in (a) Iraq and (b) Syria since the UK joined the coalition fighting against Daesh in those countries.","false","Biography information for Tim Farron","Westmorland and Lonsdale","Tim Farron","42392"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535199","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-07-14","<p>The Department has not estimated the value of its maps. They are increasingly held in digital form, in many cases issued and used digitally, and only printed as required. The accounting value of our holdings is rated as 'zero'as they have no realisable financial value due to copyright and licensing constraints. The value to Defence of the material held in the databases is impossible to quantify.</p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster",,"2016-07-14T15:35:06.773Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535199/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535199/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535199/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-07-11","Ministry of Defence: Maps","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what the estimated value is of maps held by his Department.","false","Biography information for Mr Virendra Sharma","Ealing, Southall","Mr Virendra Sharma","42313"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535200","Department for Education","false","2016-07-19","<p>We received a high number of responses to the first stage of our consultation on the principles and building blocks of the schools national funding formula. Those will inform our detailed proposals for the design of the formula, which we will put forward later this year. We must allow appropriate time to consider what would be significant reforms, and we remain committed to introducing the formula from 2017-18 so that schools can start to benefit from fairer funding as soon as possible.</p>","Crewe and Nantwich","Edward Timpson",,"2016-07-19T16:39:59.117Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535200/answer","Biography information for Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535200/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535200/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-07-11","Schools: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, when her Department plans to publish the findings of the first phase of its consultation on a national schools funding formula; and when the second phase of that consultation is planned to commence.","false","Biography information for Chuka Umunna","Streatham","Mr Chuka Umunna","42318"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535201","Department for Education","false","2016-07-20","<p>The Department does not hold this information.</p><p>Sex and relationship education (SRE) is compulsory in maintained secondary schools. Academies and free schools do not have to teach SRE but many choose to do so as part of their duty to provide a broad and balanced curriculum. When academies do teach SRE they are required through their funding agreement to have regard to the Secretary of State’s Sex and Relationship Education Guidance[1].</p><p>[1] <a href="http://www.education.gov.uk/aboutdfe/statutory/g00214676/sex-and-relationships-education-guidance" target="_blank">http://www.education.gov.uk/aboutdfe/statutory/g00214676/sex-and-relationships-education-guidance</a></p>","Crewe and Nantwich","Edward Timpson",,"2016-07-20T08:41:05.607Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535201/answer","Biography information for Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535201/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535201/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-07-11","Sex and Relationship Education","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how many (a) primary and (b) secondary academies and free schools teach sex and relationships education.","false","Biography information for Catherine West","Hornsey and Wood Green","Catherine West","42308"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535202","Department for Education","false","2016-07-19","<p>The department collects information from each local authority (LA) on the current number of school places and LA’s firm plans for the delivery of additional places over the next three years, through the annual school capacity survey (SCAP).</p><p>As at May 2015 there were 475,707 primary places and 375,888 secondary places at maintained mainstream schools across Yorkshire and Humber. At that point in time LAs across Yorkshire and Humber reported they had firm plans for delivery of an additional 17,919 places by 2017/18. The number of new places for which LAs have firm plans for delivery, through academic years 2015/16, 2016/17 and 2017/18 is available in table A7 of the attached and is available on GOV.UK at: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/school-capacity-academic-year-2014-to-2015" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/school-capacity-academic-year-2014-to-2015</a></p><p>The data represents a snapshot in time and LAs will have delivered and developed plans for many more new places since.</p>","Crewe and Nantwich","Edward Timpson",,"2016-07-19T15:46:12.017Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535202/answer","Biography information for Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535202/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535202/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-07-11","Schools: Yorkshire and the Humber","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, if she will estimate the number of school places that will be available in Yorkshire and Humber in each of the next five years.","false","Biography information for Michael Dugher","Barnsley East","Michael Dugher","42323"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535203","Department for Education","false","2016-07-21","<p>If a school believes that there is a discrepancy between how questions have been marked and the published mark scheme for Key Stage 2 National Curriculum tests, they had until 15 July 2016 to apply for a marking review. Statistics related to marking reviews will be published in November 2016.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb","42333","2016-07-21T10:06:28.38Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535203/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535203/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535203/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-07-11","National Curriculum Tests","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what proportion of key stage 2 tests in 2016 have required remarking.","false","Biography information for Christian Matheson","City of Chester","Christian Matheson","42332"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535204","Department for Education","false","2016-07-21","<p>If a school believes that there is a discrepancy between how questions have been marked and the published mark scheme for Key Stage 2 National Curriculum tests, they had until 15 July 2016 to apply for a marking review. Statistics related to marking reviews will be published in November 2016.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb","42332","2016-07-21T10:06:28.427Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535204/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535204/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535204/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-07-11","National Curriculum Tests","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how many primary schools have raised concerns with her Department on the marking of the key stage 2 reading assessment in 2016.","false","Biography information for Christian Matheson","City of Chester","Christian Matheson","42333"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535205","Department for Education","false","2016-07-20","<p>Since the Education and Adoption Act came into force in April 2016, the Secretary of State has been under a duty to make an Academy Order in respect of any maintained school that has been judged by Ofsted to be inadequate. Regional Schools Commissioners, acting on behalf of the Secretary of State, ensure that the maintained school becomes a sponsored academy as swiftly as possible, after considering the circumstances in the school, and then identifying the most suitable sponsor.</p><p>No Academy Orders have been revoked to date.</p><p>143 Academy Orders have been made since the new duty came into force. It is too soon to give an annual average of how long it has taken to match a school to a sponsor under these new arrangements.</p>","Crewe and Nantwich","Edward Timpson","42279 ; 42280","2016-07-20T08:39:20.347Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535205/answer","Biography information for Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535205/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535205/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-07-11","Academies: Sponsorship","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, (a) on how many occasions and (b) in relation to which schools since 2010 an Academy Order has been rescinded due to the inability of the Regional Schools Commissioner to secure a sponsor.","false","Biography information for Heidi Alexander","Lewisham East","Heidi Alexander","42278"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535206","Department for Education","false","2016-07-20","<p>Since the Education and Adoption Act came into force in April 2016, the Secretary of State has been under a duty to make an Academy Order in respect of any maintained school that has been judged by Ofsted to be inadequate. Regional Schools Commissioners, acting on behalf of the Secretary of State, ensure that the maintained school becomes a sponsored academy as swiftly as possible, after considering the circumstances in the school, and then identifying the most suitable sponsor.</p><p>No Academy Orders have been revoked to date.</p><p>143 Academy Orders have been made since the new duty came into force. It is too soon to give an annual average of how long it has taken to match a school to a sponsor under these new arrangements.</p>","Crewe and Nantwich","Edward Timpson","42278 ; 42280","2016-07-20T08:39:20.41Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535206/answer","Biography information for Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535206/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535206/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-07-11","Academies: Sponsorship","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what the average period of time was between an Academy Order being issued and a sponsor being named for schools in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Heidi Alexander","Lewisham East","Heidi Alexander","42279"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535207","Department for Education","false","2016-07-20","<p>Since the Education and Adoption Act came into force in April 2016, the Secretary of State has been under a duty to make an Academy Order in respect of any maintained school that has been judged by Ofsted to be inadequate. Regional Schools Commissioners, acting on behalf of the Secretary of State, ensure that the maintained school becomes a sponsored academy as swiftly as possible, after considering the circumstances in the school, and then identifying the most suitable sponsor.</p><p>No Academy Orders have been revoked to date.</p><p>143 Academy Orders have been made since the new duty came into force. It is too soon to give an annual average of how long it has taken to match a school to a sponsor under these new arrangements.</p>","Crewe and Nantwich","Edward Timpson","42278 ; 42279","2016-07-20T08:39:20.473Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535207/answer","Biography information for Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535207/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535207/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-07-11","Academies: Sponsorship","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what guidelines her Department has issued on the time to be taken by a Regional Schools Commissioner to name a sponsor for a school that has been issued with an Academy Order.","false","Biography information for Heidi Alexander","Lewisham East","Heidi Alexander","42280"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535208","Department for Education","false","2016-07-18","<p>A school should treat a pupil’s absence as authorised if a pupil is unable to attend on a day exclusively set apart for religious observance by the religious body to which their parent belongs.</p><p>This is set out in Regulation 6(2)(b)(ii) of the Education (Pupil Registration) (England) Regulations 2006, available at: <a href="http://www.legislation.gov.uk/uksi/2006/1751/regulation/6/made" target="_blank">http://www.legislation.gov.uk/uksi/2006/1751/regulation/6/made</a></p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2016-07-18T15:29:21.12Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535208/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535208/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535208/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-07-11","Schools: Festivals and Special Occasions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what provision schools make for Muslim children who want to take time off school for Eid.","false","Biography information for Rachel Reeves","Leeds West","Rachel Reeves","42284"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535209","Department for Education","false","2016-07-18","<p>The number of children and young people with a statement or education, health and care (EHC) plan who are educated at home is not specifically collected in the ‘Statements and EHC plans England: 2016’ publication[1]. However, as these children and young people will be included in the total number of children and young people with statements and EHC plans, local authorities are likely to have included these children and young people in the ‘other arrangements made by the local authority’ or ‘other arrangements made by the parent’ category.</p><p>The number of children and young people with statements or EHC plans who are not in employment, education or training (NEET) is not specifically collected in this statistical first release. Where young people have a statement or EHC plan and are NEET, they will be included in one of the other categories, e.g. ‘other arrangements made by local authority’ or ‘awaiting provision’.</p><p>There is not an exhaustive list of arrangements included in the category of ‘Other – arrangements made by the local authority in accordance with Section 319 of the Education Act 1996 or Section 61 of the Children and Families Act 2014’. The published SEN 2016 guide for local authorities[2] completing this part of the collection is as follows:</p><p>‘Section 319 of the Education Act 1996 empowers an authority to provide education for children with special educational needs “other than in school”. This may include education in centres run by social services or at home. Children would not normally be on another school register.</p><p>‘Section 61 of the Children and Families Act 2014 empowers an authority to provide education for children and young people with special educational needs “other than in school, post-16 institutions, etc”. This may include education in centres run by social services or where the local authority has named home education on an EHC plan.’</p><p> </p><p>[1] <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/statements-of-sen-and-ehc-plans-england-2016" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/statements-of-sen-and-ehc-plans-england-2016</a></p><p>[2] <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/special-educational-needs-survey-2016-guide" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/special-educational-needs-survey-2016-guide</a></p>","Crewe and Nantwich","Edward Timpson","42302","2016-07-18T13:02:20.527Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535209/answer","Biography information for Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535209/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535209/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-07-11","Special Educational Needs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how many children and young people who are either educated at home or not in employment, education or training are recorded within the statistics and analysis on statements of special educational needs and education, health and care plans in England published on 26 May 2016; and under which categories such children and young people are recorded.","false","Biography information for Dame Cheryl Gillan","Chesham and Amersham","Mrs Cheryl Gillan","42301"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535210","Department for Education","false","2016-07-18","<p>The number of children and young people with a statement or education, health and care (EHC) plan who are educated at home is not specifically collected in the ‘Statements and EHC plans England: 2016’ publication[1]. However, as these children and young people will be included in the total number of children and young people with statements and EHC plans, local authorities are likely to have included these children and young people in the ‘other arrangements made by the local authority’ or ‘other arrangements made by the parent’ category.</p><p>The number of children and young people with statements or EHC plans who are not in employment, education or training (NEET) is not specifically collected in this statistical first release. Where young people have a statement or EHC plan and are NEET, they will be included in one of the other categories, e.g. ‘other arrangements made by local authority’ or ‘awaiting provision’.</p><p>There is not an exhaustive list of arrangements included in the category of ‘Other – arrangements made by the local authority in accordance with Section 319 of the Education Act 1996 or Section 61 of the Children and Families Act 2014’. The published SEN 2016 guide for local authorities[2] completing this part of the collection is as follows:</p><p>‘Section 319 of the Education Act 1996 empowers an authority to provide education for children with special educational needs “other than in school”. This may include education in centres run by social services or at home. Children would not normally be on another school register.</p><p>‘Section 61 of the Children and Families Act 2014 empowers an authority to provide education for children and young people with special educational needs “other than in school, post-16 institutions, etc”. This may include education in centres run by social services or where the local authority has named home education on an EHC plan.’</p><p> </p><p>[1] <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/statements-of-sen-and-ehc-plans-england-2016" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/statements-of-sen-and-ehc-plans-england-2016</a></p><p>[2] <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/special-educational-needs-survey-2016-guide" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/special-educational-needs-survey-2016-guide</a></p>","Crewe and Nantwich","Edward Timpson","42301","2016-07-18T13:02:20.437Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535210/answer","Biography information for Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535210/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535210/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-07-11","Special Educational Needs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what establishment types and educational provision arrangements are included within the category of other arrangements made by local authority used in the statistics and analysis on statements of special educational needs and education, health and care plans in England published on 26 May 2016.","false","Biography information for Dame Cheryl Gillan","Chesham and Amersham","Mrs Cheryl Gillan","42302"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535211","Department for Education","false","2016-07-26","<p>There is no ‘National Allocation Scheme’, but this year we have used recruitment controls for the purpose of recruitment to Initial Teacher Training (ITT). Information on these recruitment controls can be found at: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/initial-teacher-training-itt-recruitment-controls" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/initial-teacher-training-itt-recruitment-controls</a></p><p> </p><p>In response to feedback from the sector from previous years, we changed the approach to initial teacher training (ITT) allocations for 2016-17 recruitment. The National College for Teaching and Leadership did not allocate a specific number of places to individual organisations for postgraduate ITT courses due to start in the 2016-17 academic year. Instead, eligible schools, School Centred Initial Teacher Training providers (SCITTs) and higher education institutions (HEIs) are able to recruit (subject to a limited number of controls) as many trainees as they feel they need until the overall system has recruited sufficient trainees.</p><p> </p><p>The Census data which will be published online later in 2016 will indicate the number of trainees recruited by subject.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2016-07-26T08:07:50.65Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535211/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535211/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535211/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-07-11","Teachers: Training","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what assessment her Department has made of the performance of the National Allocation Scheme relating to initial teacher training as part of National Teaching School programme.","false","Biography information for Melanie Onn","Great Grimsby","Melanie Onn","42393"
