"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535277","Home Office","false","2016-07-14","<p>Guidance for identifying and supporting victims will be published once the National Referral Mechanism pilot has concluded. The guidance is being developed in consultation with NGOs and frontline agencies.</p>","Staffordshire Moorlands","Karen Bradley",,"2016-07-14T14:53:27.367Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535277/answer","Biography information for Karen Bradley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535277/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535277/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-07-11","Slavery","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, when she plans to issue statutory guidance for identifying and supporting victims as set out in section 49 of the Modern Slavery Act 2015.","false","Biography information for Paul Blomfield","Sheffield Central","Paul Blomfield","42403"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535278","Home Office","false","2016-07-14","<p>The Home Office does not hold the specific information in the format requested. The questions cover a number of different casework operations and the information is not recorded centrally in a way which can be reported on directly.</p><p>To obtain the information would involve examining individual case records and would incur disproportionate cost. We do not currently plan to change the data that is centrally recorded and published on this category of applications.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire","42276 ; 42277","2016-07-14T15:22:11.447Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535278/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535278/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535278/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-07-11","Immigration: Families","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, if she will collect regularly statistics on the (a) number of and (b) reasons for exceptional family reunion cases relating to children where indefinite leave to remain is granted at her discretion outside of the rules.","false","Biography information for Stuart C. McDonald","Cumbernauld, Kilsyth and Kirkintilloch East","Stuart C. McDonald","42404"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535279","Home Office","false","2016-07-13","<p>In 2015/16, the Disclosure and Barring Service processed 87% of all applications within 21 days, against a target of 85%.</p><p>Some of the over four million applications received each year need to be referred to one or more police forces for further checks. There is a service level agreement between the Disclosure and Barring Service and police forces in relation to the time taken to complete these local disclosure checks.</p><p>These standards are: -</p><p>85% of police checks must be completed in 14 days;</p><p>90% of police checks must be completed in 18 days;</p><p>95% of police checks must be completed in 25 days; and - 100% of police checks must be completed in 60 days.</p>","Staffordshire Moorlands","Karen Bradley","42336","2016-07-13T15:36:32.503Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535279/answer","Biography information for Karen Bradley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535279/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535279/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-07-11","Vetting","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what her Department's target waiting time is for a Disclosure and Barring Service local intelligence check to be completed by the Metropolitan Police Service.","false","Biography information for Catherine West","Hornsey and Wood Green","Catherine West","42337"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535280","Home Office","false","2016-07-14","<p>The Home Office does not hold the specific information in the format requested. The questions cover a number of different casework operations and the information is not recorded centrally in a way which can be reported on directly.</p><p>To obtain the information would involve examining individual case records and would incur disproportionate cost. We do not currently plan to change the data that is centrally recorded and published on this category of applications.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire","42277 ; 42404","2016-07-14T15:22:11.51Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535280/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535280/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535280/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-07-11","Asylum: Families","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, if her Department will collect data on the reasons given for refusal of family reunion applications involving children and young people aged over 18 years of age.","false","Biography information for Stuart C. McDonald","Cumbernauld, Kilsyth and Kirkintilloch East","Stuart C. McDonald","42276"
