"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535282","Home Office","false","2016-07-14","<p>Anyone seeking entry or admission to the UK must on arrival establish their nationality and identity, as well as comply with other checks under the Border Force Operating Mandate.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2016-07-14T15:19:08.21Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535282/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535282/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535282/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-07-11","Immigration Controls: EU Nationals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what guidance her Department has issued to staff working at border controls in UK airports on questions which can and cannot be asked to passengers arriving in the UK with EU passports.","false","Biography information for Peter Grant","Glenrothes","Peter Grant","42307"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535283","Home Office","false","2016-07-20","<p>Her Majesty's Government announced the closure of the Tier 1 (Post Study Work) category in March 2011 and implemented its closure in April 2012, as part of a package of reforms to immigration requirements for overseas students.</p><p>We closed the Tier 1 (Post Study Work) category because too many individuals in the route were unemployed or in low-skilled work. Furthermore, too many were using the student route merely as a means to work in the UK, without any intention of study, which does not help hard-working people or our educational institutions. We have replaced it with a more selective system.</p><p>We continue to have an excellent post-study offer for graduates that helps us retain the brightest and best overseas students to undertake skilled work in the UK after their studies. In 2015, more than 6,000 international students switched from Tier 4 to Tier 2 from within the UK. This is up from around 5,500 grants in 2014, and around 4,000 grants in 2013. Unlike former post-study work schemes, these students will all be moving into skilled employment with employers who have appropriate sponsorship duties placed upon them.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-07-20T13:47:35.677Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535283/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535283/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535283/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-07-11","Overseas Students: Scotland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, if she will make it her policy to reintroduce the post-study work visa in Scotland.","false","Biography information for Natalie McGarry","Glasgow East","Natalie McGarry","42316"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535284","Home Office","false","2016-07-20","<p>From June 2015 to May 2016, the average time taken to complete Disclosure checks by the Metropolitan Police Service (MPS) was 94 days and for the police as a whole, 22 days.</p><p>The Disclosure and Barring Service (DBS) is working closely with the small number of forces, including the MPS, whose performance does not meet turnaround time targets. The performance of police disclosure units is an operational issue for individual police forces and the MPS has established a Gold Group to oversee the recovery plan which they have in place to reduce the time taken. I have made clear to the MPS that its current delays must be addressed as a matter of priority and I continue to maintain close oversight of the progress being made.</p>","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton","42335","2016-07-20T13:14:58.92Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535284/answer","Biography information for Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535284/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535284/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-07-11","Vetting","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what the average waiting time is for a Disclosure and Barring Service local intelligence check to be completed by the Metropolitan Police Service.","false","Biography information for Catherine West","Hornsey and Wood Green","Catherine West","42334"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535285","Home Office","false","2016-07-20","<p>From June 2015 to May 2016, the average time taken to complete Disclosure checks by the Metropolitan Police Service (MPS) was 94 days and for the police as a whole, 22 days.</p><p>The Disclosure and Barring Service (DBS) is working closely with the small number of forces, including the MPS, whose performance does not meet turnaround time targets. The performance of police disclosure units is an operational issue for individual police forces and the MPS has established a Gold Group to oversee the recovery plan which they have in place to reduce the time taken. I have made clear to the MPS that its current delays must be addressed as a matter of priority and I continue to maintain close oversight of the progress being made.</p>","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton","42334","2016-07-20T13:14:58.98Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535285/answer","Biography information for Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535285/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535285/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-07-11","Vetting","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what the average waiting time is for a Disclosure and Barring Service local intelligence check to be completed by the police.","false","Biography information for Catherine West","Hornsey and Wood Green","Catherine West","42335"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535286","Home Office","false","2016-07-13","<p>In 2015/16, the Disclosure and Barring Service processed 87% of all applications within 21 days, against a target of 85%.</p><p>Some of the over four million applications received each year need to be referred to one or more police forces for further checks. There is a service level agreement between the Disclosure and Barring Service and police forces in relation to the time taken to complete these local disclosure checks.</p><p>These standards are: -</p><p>85% of police checks must be completed in 14 days;</p><p>90% of police checks must be completed in 18 days;</p><p>95% of police checks must be completed in 25 days; and - 100% of police checks must be completed in 60 days.</p>","Staffordshire Moorlands","Karen Bradley","42337","2016-07-13T15:36:32.583Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535286/answer","Biography information for Karen Bradley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535286/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535286/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-07-11","Vetting","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what her Department's target waiting time is for a Disclosure and Barring Service local intelligence check to be completed by the police.","false","Biography information for Catherine West","Hornsey and Wood Green","Catherine West","42336"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535287","House of Commons Commission","false","2016-07-19","<p>A procurement process for a new contract for screening mail received by hon. Members is currently underway. A full review of the security arrangements and contract specification forms part of that process. This review is based on advice from the Centre for the Protection of National Infrastructure (CPNI) as well as on a national standard specification for mail screening (PAS 97:2015).</p><p>Following an incident, the Parliamentary Security Department has recently revised and reissued guidance to Members and staff on what to do following receipt of a suspicious letter or package.</p><p>We do not comment in public on details of security arrangements. The Deputy Director of Security (Delivery) would be happy to discuss these arrangements in more detail with the hon. Member.</p>","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake",,"2016-07-19T16:04:26.837Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535287/answer","Biography information for Tom Brake","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535287/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535287/answer",,,,,"18","House of Commons Commission","House of Commons Commission","2016-07-11","Members: Security","1","House of Commons","To ask the Rt. hon. Member for Carshalton and Wallington representing the House of Commons Commission, what recent assessment the Commission has made of the security arrangements for screening mail received by hon. Members of each House of Parliament.","false","Biography information for Andrew Stephenson","Pendle","Andrew Stephenson","42380"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535288","Department for International Development","false","2016-07-14","<p>The UK government is committed to supporting the achievement of the Global Goals in countries which receive UK Aid and is prioritising programmes to ensure that everyone has access to sustainable drinking water, sanitation and hygiene (WASH). From 2010 to 2015 DFID supported 60 million people to gain access to sustainable WASH. We are committed to supporting a further 60 million people gain access to sustainable WASH up to the end of 2020. Providing a safe and reliable drinking water and sanitation is a key element of our work across all our country programmes.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd",,"2016-07-14T07:11:19.5Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535288/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535288/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535288/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-07-11","Developing Countries: Drinking Water","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what steps she is taking to ensure that water safe for drinking is available in countries which receive aid from her Department; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","42370"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535289","Department for International Development","false","2016-07-15","<p>WaterAid received over £24million of DFID funding from April 2013 to March 2016. We have so far committed £4.7million in funding for April 2016 to March 2018.</p><p>DFID funding has contributed to WaterAid directly reaching more than 2 million people with safe water and over 3 million people with sanitation in the last year alone. In addition, our Programme Partnership Arrangement (PPA) funding, effective from 2011 until the end of 2016, enabled WaterAid to improve their overall organisational effectiveness by supporting them to develop stronger Monitoring and Evaluation systems; improve their Value for Money framework and supported growth and innovation throughout the organisation.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd","42385 ; 42387","2016-07-15T10:41:55.867Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535289/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535289/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535289/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-07-11","Water Aid","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what estimate she has made of the yearly contributions by her Department to WaterAid in each of the next five years; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","42386"
