"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535292","Department for International Development","false","2016-07-15","<p>We are deeply concerned by the deterioration in the security situation in South Sudan. This will make it even harder for aid to reach the millions of South Sudanese displaced from their homes and the almost 5 million, nearly half the population, at risk of severe food insecurity. The UK is taking a lead role. We have contributed £242million to the humanitarian crisis since the outbreak of conflict in December 2013, along with an additional £93million to support South Sudanese refugees in the region. But ultimately the South Sudanese leaders must take responsibility for respecting the ceasefires and protecting their people.</p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd",,"2016-07-15T10:40:51.64Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535292/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535292/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535292/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-07-11","South Sudan","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what recent assessment she has made of the humanitarian situation in South Sudan.","false","Biography information for Stephen Gethins","North East Fife","Stephen Gethins","42424"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535293","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-07-14","<p>Until 31 March 2013 the Ministry of Justice published twice yearly updates on coroners’ reports to prevent future deaths. The relevant information can be found in the links below to the four reports which cover the period 1 April 2011 to 31 March 2013:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/summary-of-reports-and-responses-under-rule-43-of-the-coroners-rules" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/summary-of-reports-and-responses-under-rule-43-of-the-coroners-rules</a></p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/summary-of-reports-and-responses-under-rule-43-of-the-coroners-rules--10" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/summary-of-reports-and-responses-under-rule-43-of-the-coroners-rules--10</a></p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/summary-of-reports-and-responses-under-rule-43-of-the-coroners-rules-1984" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/summary-of-reports-and-responses-under-rule-43-of-the-coroners-rules-1984</a></p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/summary-of-reports-and-responses-under-rule-43-of-the-coroners-rules--12" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/summary-of-reports-and-responses-under-rule-43-of-the-coroners-rules--12</a></p><p> </p><p>Reports since 1 April 2013 are posted on the Chief Coroner’s website at <a href="https://www.judiciary.gov.uk/related-offices-and-bodies/office-chief-coroner/pfd-reports/" target="_blank">https://www.judiciary.gov.uk/related-offices-and-bodies/office-chief-coroner/pfd-reports/</a></p><p> </p><p>Any review of the law relating to the operation of on-line prescribing would be the responsibility of the Department of Health.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage","42441","2016-07-14T16:26:07.577Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535293/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535293/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535293/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-07-11","Pharmacy: Internet","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many coroners' reports in the last five years have cited over-prescribing by online pharmacies as a (a) cause and (b) contributory cause of death; and what action the Government has taken as a result of those reports.","false","Biography information for Helen Jones","Warrington North","Helen Jones","42440"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535294","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-07-14","<p>Until 31 March 2013 the Ministry of Justice published twice yearly updates on coroners’ reports to prevent future deaths. The relevant information can be found in the links below to the four reports which cover the period 1 April 2011 to 31 March 2013:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/summary-of-reports-and-responses-under-rule-43-of-the-coroners-rules" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/summary-of-reports-and-responses-under-rule-43-of-the-coroners-rules</a></p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/summary-of-reports-and-responses-under-rule-43-of-the-coroners-rules--10" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/summary-of-reports-and-responses-under-rule-43-of-the-coroners-rules--10</a></p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/summary-of-reports-and-responses-under-rule-43-of-the-coroners-rules-1984" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/summary-of-reports-and-responses-under-rule-43-of-the-coroners-rules-1984</a></p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/summary-of-reports-and-responses-under-rule-43-of-the-coroners-rules--12" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/summary-of-reports-and-responses-under-rule-43-of-the-coroners-rules--12</a></p><p> </p><p>Reports since 1 April 2013 are posted on the Chief Coroner’s website at <a href="https://www.judiciary.gov.uk/related-offices-and-bodies/office-chief-coroner/pfd-reports/" target="_blank">https://www.judiciary.gov.uk/related-offices-and-bodies/office-chief-coroner/pfd-reports/</a></p><p> </p><p>Any review of the law relating to the operation of on-line prescribing would be the responsibility of the Department of Health.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage","42440","2016-07-14T16:26:07.687Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535294/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535294/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535294/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-07-11","Pharmacy: Internet","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, if he will undertake a review of the law relating to the operation of online pharmacies; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Helen Jones","Warrington North","Helen Jones","42441"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535295","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-07-19","<p>The post-implementation review of the coroner reforms consultation closed on 31 December 2015. A response to the consultation will be published in due course.</p><p> </p><p>We received 214 responses to the review from current coronial officer holders. No respondents indicated that they were former coroners.</p>","Bracknell","Dr Phillip Lee","42376","2016-07-19T14:35:33.467Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535295/answer","Biography information for Dr Phillip Lee","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535295/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535295/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-07-11","Coroners: Reform","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many (a) former and (b) current coroners responded to the consultation on the post-implementation review of the coroner reforms in the Coroners and Justice Act 2009.","false","Biography information for Andrew Stephenson","Pendle","Andrew Stephenson","42382"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535296","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-07-19","<p>Justice Ministers have received representations from the Jewish and Muslim communities about coroners out of hours’ services and have met representatives from these communities. We recognise the importance of an out of hours service and have worked with the police and local authorities to this end.</p><p> </p><p>Regulation 4 of the Coroners (Investigations) Regulations 2013 requires coroners to be available at all times to address matters relating to an investigation into a death which must be dealt with immediately and cannot wait until the next working day. This is particularly important in cases of homicide and mass fatalities. Coroners also make themselves available if needed in cases involving organ and tissue donation.</p>","Bracknell","Dr Phillip Lee","42384","2016-07-19T14:48:57.98Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535296/answer","Biography information for Dr Phillip Lee","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535296/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535296/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-07-11","Coroners","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what representations he has received from minority faith groups since July 2013 on the availability of coroners at all times.","false","Biography information for Andrew Stephenson","Pendle","Andrew Stephenson","42383"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535297","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-07-19","<p>Justice Ministers have received representations from the Jewish and Muslim communities about coroners out of hours’ services and have met representatives from these communities. We recognise the importance of an out of hours service and have worked with the police and local authorities to this end.</p><p> </p><p>Regulation 4 of the Coroners (Investigations) Regulations 2013 requires coroners to be available at all times to address matters relating to an investigation into a death which must be dealt with immediately and cannot wait until the next working day. This is particularly important in cases of homicide and mass fatalities. Coroners also make themselves available if needed in cases involving organ and tissue donation.</p>","Bracknell","Dr Phillip Lee","42383","2016-07-19T14:48:58.06Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535297/answer","Biography information for Dr Phillip Lee","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535297/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535297/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-07-11","Coroners","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what assessment he has made of the availability of coroners at all times to address matters which must be dealt with immediately under the provisions of the Coroners and Justice Act 2009.","false","Biography information for Andrew Stephenson","Pendle","Andrew Stephenson","42384"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535298","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-07-19","<p>The post-implementation review of the coroner reforms consultation closed on 31 December 2015. A response to the consultation will be published in due course.</p><p> </p><p>We received 214 responses to the review from current coronial officer holders. No respondents indicated that they were former coroners.</p>","Bracknell","Dr Phillip Lee","42382","2016-07-19T14:35:33.393Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535298/answer","Biography information for Dr Phillip Lee","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535298/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535298/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-07-11","Coroners: Reform","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what progress his Department has made on preparing a response to the consultation on the post-implementation review of the coroner reforms in the Coroners and Justice Act 2009; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Andrew Stephenson","Pendle","Andrew Stephenson","42376"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535299","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-07-19","<p>We will set out our proposals for a Bill of Rights in due course. We will fully consult on our proposals.</p>","North East Hertfordshire","Sir Oliver Heald",,"2016-07-19T14:17:37.387Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535299/answer","Biography information for Sir Oliver Heald","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535299/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535299/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-07-11","Bill of Rights","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what the timetable is for the introduction of proposals for a British Bill of Rights.","false","Biography information for Neil Coyle","Bermondsey and Old Southwark","Neil Coyle","42369"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535300","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-07-14","<p>One year proven reoffending for juveniles cautioned, convicted at court for a non-custodial sentence or released from custody for a serious offence in financial years 2011/12, 2012/13 and 2013/14.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p>Apr 2011 to Mar 2012</p></td><td><p>Apr 2012 to Mar 2013</p></td><td><p>Apr 2013 to Mar 2014</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Juvenile offenders with a serious index offence</strong></p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Proportion of offenders who reoffend (%)</p></td><td><p><strong>39.4</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>39.9</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>39.6</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Number of reoffenders</p></td><td><p>2,827</p></td><td><p>2,272</p></td><td><p>1,783</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Number of offenders in cohort</p></td><td><p>7,172</p></td><td><p>5,693</p></td><td><p>4,501</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>The seriousness definition used can be found in Annex A of the following link:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/496925/proven-reoffending-definitions-measurement.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/496925/proven-reoffending-definitions-measurement.pdf</a></p><p> </p><p><strong>Data Sources </strong></p><p>These figures have been derived from administrative IT systems which, as with any large scale recording system, are subject to possible errors with data entry and processing. A certain proportion of offenders who could not be matched to the Police National Computer (PNC) are excluded from the offender cohort. Therefore, these numbers do not represent all proven offenders.</p>","South West Bedfordshire","Andrew Selous",,"2016-07-14T16:21:07.723Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535300/answer","Biography information for Andrew Selous","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535300/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535300/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-07-11","Young Offenders: Reoffenders","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many juveniles convicted of serious offences have reoffended in each of the last three financial years.","false","Biography information for Gloria De Piero","Ashfield","Gloria De Piero","42295"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535301","Scotland Office","false","2016-07-15","<p>The United Kingdom is fundamentally strong and is well-placed to rise to the challenges we face.</p><p> </p><p>Following the result of the referendum on the United Kingdom’s membership of the European Union, our focus now needs to be working together as Team UK, to achieve the best deal for both Scotland and the United Kingdom in the negotiations with the EU.</p>","Dumfriesshire, Clydesdale and Tweeddale","David Mundell",,"2016-07-15T11:45:53.407Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535301/answer","Biography information for David Mundell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535301/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535301/answer",,,,,"2","Scotland","Scotland","2016-07-11","Brexit: Scotland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Scotland, what recent assessment he has made of the potential effect on Scotland of the UK leaving the EU.","false","Biography information for Natalie McGarry","Glasgow East","Natalie McGarry","42396"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535302","Scotland Office","false","2016-07-14","<p>The Government set out our assessment of the impact of the welfare policies in the Welfare Reform and Work Act on 20 July 2015, with similar assessments for previous changes.</p>","Dumfriesshire, Clydesdale and Tweeddale","David Mundell",,"2016-07-14T13:27:38.717Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535302/answer","Biography information for David Mundell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535302/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535302/answer",,,,,"2","Scotland","Scotland","2016-07-11","Welfare State: Scotland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Scotland, what recent assessment he has made of the effect of welfare reform, including benefit sanctions and work capability assessments, on claimants in (a) Glasgow and (b) Scotland.","false","Biography information for Natalie McGarry","Glasgow East","Natalie McGarry","42367"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535303","Department for Transport","false","2016-07-13","<p>I am happy to provide the Honourable Member with full details about the documents held by the Department relating to the disappearance of Rebecca Coriam and have asked officials to write to him with this information.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-07-13T15:14:44.147Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535303/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535303/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535303/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-07-11","Rebecca Coriam","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, if he will provide a schedule of documents held by his Department relating to the disappearance of Rebecca Coriam from the Disney Wonder cruise ship in March 2011 and the investigation into that disappearance.","false","Biography information for Christian Matheson","City of Chester","Christian Matheson","42329"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535304","Department for Transport","false","2016-07-13","<p>The replacement of Pacer trains across the Northern network will be completed by December 2019, although the timing of when this will occur on individual lines will be a matter for Northern Rail.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2016-07-13T11:31:00.237Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535304/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535304/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535304/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-07-11","Tees Valley Railway Line","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, by what date his Department expects the replacement of Pacer trains on the Tees Valley Line to be completed.","false","Biography information for Anna Turley","Redcar","Anna Turley","42343"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535305","Department for Transport","false","2016-07-13","<p>As part of the new franchise award, the Northern franchisee will be required before October 2017 to undertake a feasibility study, identifying options for journey time improvements across the whole network, including services in the North East. This will include possible changes to existing infrastructure, improvements to rolling stock capability and reliability and the implementing of changes to service patterns.</p><p> </p><p>Any resulting changes would be in addition to the local benefits secured as part of the franchise including the withdrawal of pacer trains and the refurbishment of all the existing carriages retained in the franchise long term.</p><p> </p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2016-07-13T11:34:46.463Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535305/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535305/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535305/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-07-11","Tees Valley Railway Line","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what steps his Department is taking to improve journey times on the Tees Valley Line.","false","Biography information for Anna Turley","Redcar","Anna Turley","42344"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535306","Department for Transport","false","2016-07-13","<p>The Northern franchise was recently awarded to Arriva Rail North, who took over operations in April 2016. Arriva Rail North sets out its policy for providing assistance to disabled passengers and passengers of reduced mobility in its Disabled People’s Protection Policy (DPPP). Publishing commitments to on-board assistance in a DPPP is a passenger train operating licence requirement and is approved by the Office of Rail and Road (ORR). Arriva Rail North is also required to participate in the national Passenger Assist scheme for pre-booking assistance.</p><p> </p><p>‘Pacer’ trains operated by Arriva Rail North on the Tees Valley Line will be replaced ahead of the 2020 accessibility compliance deadline. From that date, all trains operated by Arriva Rail North will have to be compliant with the accessibility standards mandated by the Persons of Reduced Mobility Technical Specification for Interoperability (PRM-TSI). While Pacers do not meet the standards set out in the PRM-TSI, they do offer wheelchair spaces, audio announcements and manual boarding ramps to assist disabled passengers and persons of reduced mobility when travelling.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2016-07-13T11:40:48.713Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535306/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535306/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535306/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-07-11","Tees Valley Railway Line","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what steps his Department is taking to support disabled passengers and passengers of reduced mobility on the Tees Valley Line for the duration of operation of Pacer trains.","false","Biography information for Anna Turley","Redcar","Anna Turley","42345"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535307","Department for Transport","false","2016-07-14","<p>The table below sets out the spend on HS2 project in each year since 2009/10. Data for 2015/16 is provisional and is currently not included, pending publication of the HS2 Ltd Accounts shortly at GOV.UK, which will set out the precise level of expenditure for 2015/16.</p><p><em> </em></p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><em> </em></p></td><td><p><em>2009/10<br> £m</em></p></td><td><p><em>2010/11<br> £m</em></p></td><td><p><em>2011/12<br> £m</em></p></td><td><p><em>2012/13<br> £m</em></p></td><td><p><em>2013/14<br> £m</em></p></td><td><p><em>2014/15<br> £m</em></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><em>Total HS2</em></p></td><td><p><em>9.43</em></p></td><td><p><em>24.3</em></p></td><td><p><em>54</em></p></td><td><p><em>207.6</em></p></td><td><p><em>318.2</em></p></td><td><p><em>362.7</em></p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p> </p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-07-14T07:09:55.783Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535307/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535307/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535307/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-07-11","High Speed 2 Railway Line","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what the total expenditure on the High Speed 2 project has been in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Dame Cheryl Gillan","Chesham and Amersham","Mrs Cheryl Gillan","42287"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535308","Department for Transport","false","2016-07-14","<p>Construction is expected to begin in 2017.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-07-14T07:12:58.947Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535308/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535308/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535308/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-07-11","High Speed 2 Railway Line","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what the planned start date is for construction of High Speed 2 Phase One.","false","Biography information for Dame Cheryl Gillan","Chesham and Amersham","Mrs Cheryl Gillan","42288"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535309","Department for Transport","false","2016-07-14","<p>It is for the rail industry to ensure compliance with the requirements of the Consumer Rights Act when the services provisions of the Act come into force. Train companies, working with the Association of Train Operating Companies (ATOC), are currently reviewing their working practices to ensure that this is the case. The Office of Rail and Road (ORR) is a statutory enforcement body for the Consumer Rights Act for this sector.</p><p> </p><p>The Department for Transport, ATOC and the ORR are working together to co-ordinate industry wide improvements in the way that rail passenger compensations schemes are publicised and administered.</p><p> </p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2016-07-14T07:46:19.72Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535309/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535309/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535309/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-07-11","Railways","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what progress has been made by his Department and train operating companies on ensuring compliance with the relevant legislative provisions by the expiry date of the (Commencement No. 3, Transitional Provisions, Savings and Consequential Amendments) (Amendment) Order 2016 in October 2016.","false","Biography information for Peter Kyle","Hove","Peter Kyle","42304"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535310","Department for Transport","false","2016-07-14","<p>Both the long tunnel options between Darenth and South Ockenden would have a nominal capacity of approximately 8,000 vehicles per hour. In the morning peak hour at the year of opening in 2025, the (a) shorter tunnel option through junctions 2 and 30 on the M25 would have an initial forecast usage of 5,600 vehicles per hour and for (b) 3,400 for the longer beyond junction tunnel option.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2016-07-14T07:26:55.027Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535310/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535310/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535310/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-07-11","River Thames: Tunnels","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, pursuant to the Answer of 23 May 2016 to Question 37232, what assessment his Department made of the potential vehicular capacity of the two long tunnel options for the Lower Thames Crossing connected either (a) through junctions 2 and 30 on the M25 or (b) by direct connection to the motorway beyond the junctions.","false","Biography information for Adam Holloway","Gravesham","Adam Holloway","42305"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535311","Department for Transport","false","2016-07-14","<p>At this stage, we have not developed plans for changes to primary road traffic legislation other than relating to motor vehicle insurance for automated vehicles. We have also announced plans to change the Highway Code and regulations to support the safe use of advanced driver assistance systems (ADAS). The Centre for Connected and Autonomous Vehicles launched a consultation on these issues on 11 July.</p><p> </p><p>We will consider further legislative, regulatory, and guidance changes as ADAS and automated vehicles continue to develop and reach the market, so that people and businesses can safely take advantage of the benefits that they offer.</p><p> </p><p>We do not consider that legislative change is needed to facilitate testing of automated vehicle technologies; testing of automated vehicle technologies can be carried out on any UK road as long as carried out in line with UK traffic laws and guidance – further details are set out in the <em>Code of practice for testing of automated vehicle technologies</em> - <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/automated-vehicle-technologies-testing-code-of-practice" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/automated-vehicle-technologies-testing-code-of-practice</a>.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-07-14T06:42:41.58Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535311/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535311/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535311/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-07-11","Driverless Vehicles","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, whether his Department plans to include provisions in the Modern Transport Bill to (a) develop a licensing regime for the sale of safe driverless vehicles and (b) establish regulations for driverless vehicles in the testing phase.","false","Biography information for Richard Burden","Birmingham, Northfield","Richard Burden","42306"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535312","Department for Transport","false","2016-07-13","<p>In Euston, HS2 Ltd have committed to producing a quarterly newsletter, the first newsletter was circulated in May 2016 to over 21,000 homes in the Camden area. The newsletter includes information about HS2, project updates, highlights key milestones and publicises upcoming engagement activities.</p><p><br> More widely HS2 Ltd plan to publish community newsletters across the Phase One route. The first series of these newsletters is scheduled for autumn 2016.</p><p> </p><p>Phase Two is at a much earlier stage of development and HS2 Ltd are working closely with existing community engagement forums to ensure people are kept update with the latest information. HS2 Ltd anticipate publishing a community newsletter following a route announcement.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-07-13T15:11:25.467Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535312/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535312/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535312/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-07-11","High Speed 2 Railway Line","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, with reference to the Report of the HS2 Residents' Commissioner, published in May 2016, what steps his Department and HS2 Ltd have taken to introduce a newsletter for affected residents.","false","Biography information for Dame Cheryl Gillan","Chesham and Amersham","Mrs Cheryl Gillan","42327"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535313","Department for Transport","false","2016-07-13","<p>HS2 Ltd’s most recent engagement with the Amersham and Chesham community took place at the Amersham Town Carnival on Saturday 9<sup>th</sup> July, and was part of the project’s more localised approach to community engagement. The HS2 stall presented local information on the project, and was attended by around 180 residents from the Amersham / Chesham community.</p><p> </p><p>HS2 Ltd plans to attend similar existing community events across the Phase One route during the summer months, and is also drawing up a schedule of HS2 Ltd run community events, expected to be delivered in the autumn. Amersham and Chesham will be included as part of this exercise. Further details will be made available once the next event is confirmed.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-07-13T11:18:28.237Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535313/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535313/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535313/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-07-11","High Speed 2 Railway Line: Chesham and Amersham","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, when and where the next community engagement event for High Speed 2 Phase One in Chesham and Amersham constituency will take place.","false","Biography information for Dame Cheryl Gillan","Chesham and Amersham","Mrs Cheryl Gillan","42324"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535314","Department for Transport","false","2016-07-13","<p>Finalising the construction timetable for works in this area will be the responsibility of the Main Works Contractor when they are appointed following Royal Assent. An indicative construction programme for Chesham and Amersham is set out in Volume 2 of the Environmental Statement (ES) - CFA reports 8-9. This indicates advanced works commencing in the first quarter of 2017, with civil engineering works commencing in the fourth quarter of 2017.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-07-13T15:07:03.313Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535314/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535314/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535314/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-07-11","High Speed 2 Railway Line: Chesham and Amersham","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, when he expects the timetable for construction of High Speed 2 Phase One in Chesham and Amersham constituency to be published.","false","Biography information for Dame Cheryl Gillan","Chesham and Amersham","Mrs Cheryl Gillan","42326"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535315","Department for Transport","false","2016-07-13","<p>There are two Need to Sell applications from the Chesham and Amersham constituency which are currently under consideration.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-07-13T15:03:04.447Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535315/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535315/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535315/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-07-11","High Speed 2 Railway Line: Chesham and Amersham","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how many Need to Sell cases in Chesham and Amersham constituency are yet to be finalised.","false","Biography information for Dame Cheryl Gillan","Chesham and Amersham","Mrs Cheryl Gillan","42325"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535316","Department for Transport","false","2016-07-14","<p>The negotiation for Britain's future relationship with the European Union will begin under the new Prime Minister, and we now have to look at all the detailed arrangements. In the meantime, the Department will continue to work to deliver the Government agenda, including HS2.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-07-14T07:02:16.463Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535316/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535316/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535316/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-07-11","High Speed 2 Railway Line","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what assessment he has made of the potential effect of the UK leaving the EU on the construction of High Speed 2 from Birmingham to Manchester and Leeds.","false","Biography information for Gloria De Piero","Ashfield","Gloria De Piero","42303"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535317","Department for Transport","false","2016-07-14","<p>It is for Lancashire County Council, as the transport authority for Ribble Valley, to decide how to allocate funding for public transport, in consultation with its districts and communities. The County Council has received £6.054m from the Integrated Transport Block for 2016/17. In addition, £1.86m of Bus Operators Services Grant (BSOG) has been provided to support bus services.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2016-07-14T07:07:24.663Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535317/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535317/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535317/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-07-11","Public Transport: Ribble Valley","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what assessment he has made of the potential effect on the travelling public of proposed reductions in spending on public transport in Ribble Valley.","false","Biography information for Mr Nigel Evans","Ribble Valley","Mr Nigel Evans","42427"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535318","Women and Equalities","false","2016-07-14","<p>The Equality and Human Rights Commission is an independent body. It makes its own decisions about the allocation of its resources and its procedures for planning changes to its staffing against its business needs as set out in its one-year Business Plan and three-year Strategic Plan.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage","42432","2016-07-14T14:01:13.033Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535318/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535318/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535318/answer",,,,,"31","Women and Equalities","Women and Equalities","2016-07-11","Equality and Human Rights Commission: Redundancy","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for Women and Equalities, if she will recommend that the Equality and Human Rights Commission should commission an equality impact assessment of any future job losses at the Commission.","false","Biography information for Debbie Abrahams","Oldham East and Saddleworth","Debbie Abrahams","42430"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535319","Women and Equalities","false","2016-07-14","<p>The Equality and Human Rights Commission is an independent body. It makes its own decisions about the allocation of its resources and its procedures for planning changes to its staffing against its business needs as set out in its one-year Business Plan and three-year Strategic Plan.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage","42430","2016-07-14T14:01:13.11Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535319/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535319/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535319/answer",,,,,"31","Women and Equalities","Women and Equalities","2016-07-11","Equality and Human Rights Commission: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for Women and Equalities, what assessment she has made of the extent to which current and planned staffing levels at the Equality and Human Rights Commission are sufficient to enable the Commission to fulfil its statutory obligations.","false","Biography information for Debbie Abrahams","Oldham East and Saddleworth","Debbie Abrahams","42432"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535320","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-07-14","<p>I have not had any meetings with the Equality and Human Rights Commission (EHRC) to discuss its employment of disabled people.</p><p>The Office for Disability Issues has frequent communication with the EHRC who are observers at the bi-annual Fulfilling Potential Forum that I chair which is attended by a range of disability-related stakeholders. Officials from the Office for Disability Issues are also in regular contact with the EHRC in relation to the UN Convention on the Rights of Disabled People, attending quarterly Treaty Monitoring review meetings.</p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson",,"2016-07-14T13:15:30.197Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535320/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535320/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535320/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-07-11","Equality and Human Rights Commission: Recruitment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, whether he has had discussions with the Equality and Human Rights Commission on its employment of disabled people.","false","Biography information for Debbie Abrahams","Oldham East and Saddleworth","Debbie Abrahams","42431"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535321","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-07-14","<p>I refer the honourable gentleman to my response to his question dated 31 May 2016. Information regarding claims and awards in respect of a particular disease or vaccine is unavailable.</p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson",,"2016-07-14T11:19:09.773Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535321/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535321/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535321/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-07-11","Whooping Cough: Vaccination","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, pursuant to the Answer of 11 July 2016 to Question 41943, how many people have (a) claimed and (b) received payment under the vaccine damages payment scheme in respect of a vaccine used for whooping cough.","false","Biography information for Richard Burden","Birmingham, Northfield","Richard Burden","42446"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535322","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-07-14","<p>The consultation “Self-sufficient local government: 100% business rates retention”, published 5 July 2016, sets out that the Government will consider giving more responsibility to councils in England to support older people with care needs – including people who, under the current system, would be supported through Attendance Allowance.</p><p>Any new responsibilities would be matched by the transfer of equivalent spending power. Any new policy would not affect existing claimants or any passported support they receive, including those already in receipt of Attendance Allowance due to the special rules in place for the terminally ill. Any localisation proposals would not affect those already in receipt of Attendance Allowance who currently live outside the UK. Those claiming or in receipt of Disability Living Allowance or Personal Independence Payment would not be affected by any change.</p><p>The consultation “Self-sufficient local government: 100% business rates retention” closes at 12.00am on 26 September 2016, and is available here: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/consultations/self-sufficient-local-government-100-business-rates-retention" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/consultations/self-sufficient-local-government-100-business-rates-retention</a>.</p><p>This is an open consultation and all interested parties are invited to respond. The Government would consult further, including on any models and the impacts associated with them, in good time if any changes are proposed.</p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson","42359 ; 42361 ; 42363 ; 42365","2016-07-14T15:01:34.387Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535322/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535322/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535322/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-07-11","Attendance Allowance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, when his Department plans to conduct an impact assessment of its proposal to pass responsibility for attendance allowance funding to local authorities.","false","Biography information for Neil Coyle","Bermondsey and Old Southwark","Neil Coyle","42341"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535323","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-07-14","<p>The consultation “Self-sufficient local government: 100% business rates retention”, published 5 July 2016, sets out that the Government will consider giving more responsibility to councils in England to support older people with care needs – including people who, under the current system, would be supported through Attendance Allowance.</p><p>Any new responsibilities would be matched by the transfer of equivalent spending power. Any new policy would not affect existing claimants or any passported support they receive, including those already in receipt of Attendance Allowance due to the special rules in place for the terminally ill. Any localisation proposals would not affect those already in receipt of Attendance Allowance who currently live outside the UK. Those claiming or in receipt of Disability Living Allowance or Personal Independence Payment would not be affected by any change.</p><p>The consultation “Self-sufficient local government: 100% business rates retention” closes at 12.00am on 26 September 2016, and is available here: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/consultations/self-sufficient-local-government-100-business-rates-retention" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/consultations/self-sufficient-local-government-100-business-rates-retention</a>.</p><p>This is an open consultation and all interested parties are invited to respond. The Government would consult further, including on any models and the impacts associated with them, in good time if any changes are proposed.</p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson","42341 ; 42361 ; 42363 ; 42365","2016-07-14T15:01:34.467Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535323/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535323/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/535323/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-07-11","Attendance Allowance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, whether disabled people who are over state retirement age and who claim personal independence payment or disability living allowance will be affected by the proposal to transfer attendance allowance funding to councils.","false","Biography information for Neil Coyle","Bermondsey and Old Southwark","Neil Coyle","42359"
