"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533911","Home Office","false","2016-07-21","<p>Border Force and its partner organisations are well prepared to counter attempts by migrants to use small boats to circumvent border security and enter the UK illegally. A number of counter-measures have been put in place to detect and deter this activity, including the coordination of maritime security assets, so that maximum coverage at sea is delivered that ensures assets are in the right place at the right time.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford",,"2016-07-21T16:20:42.737Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533911/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533911/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533911/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-07-08","Territorial Waters: Security","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they are investigating the use of University Royal Naval Unit craft and the Maritime Volunteer Service to increase the number of platforms available for security of UK territorial seas.","false","Biography information for Lord West of Spithead",,"Lord West of Spithead","HL1092"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533912","Home Office","false","2016-07-21","<p>The National Maritime Information Centre (NMIC) facilitates information exchange between government departments and agencies. Command and control of assets is administered by the respective organisations that are represented in the NMIC.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford",,"2016-07-21T16:21:49.647Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533912/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533912/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533912/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-07-08","Territorial Waters: Security","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether the National Maritime Intelligence Centre has any command and control authority over assets available for security of UK territorial seas.","false","Biography information for Lord West of Spithead",,"Lord West of Spithead","HL1093"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533552","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-07-13","<p>I refer the hon. Member to the previous answer he references, in particular:</p><p>“Operating across split sites, in the context of a smaller workforce overall, would make it harder to quickly redeploy people to a different team or policy area, or for someone to be able to respond to an unpredictable or unusual demand for more intensive engagement with Ministers or Parliament.”</p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2016-07-13T09:35:59.767Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533552/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533552/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533552/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-07-07","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills: Reorganisation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, pursuant to the Answer of 13 June 2016 to Question 39359, on Business, Innovation and Skills reorganisation, what problems Ministers have encountered engaging with officials of his Department not based in London.","false","Biography information for Paul Blomfield","Sheffield Central","Paul Blomfield","42128"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533553","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-07-20","<p>As my right hon. Friend the Prime Minister has made clear, while the UK remains a member of the EU, current EU funding and collaboration arrangements continue unchanged, including those that apply to students, researchers, and businesses. I am in close contact with Commissioner Moedas on the topic of Horizon 2020 funding, and I met with the Italian Minister for Education, Universities and Research on 11 July.</p><p>The UK is world-class in research and innovation and we play a leading role in major European and international collaboration, including ESA and CERN.</p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson","42196 ; 42202","2016-07-20T14:47:38.607Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533553/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533553/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533553/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-07-07","Universities","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what assessment he has made of the effect of the vote to leave the EU on academic collaboration.","false","Biography information for Daniel Zeichner","Cambridge","Daniel Zeichner","42184"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533554","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-07-14","<p>The Department for Business, Innovation and Skills is only able to provide information on overall funding made available for adult learning provision. It does not hold information on learners who pay for provision.</p>","Grantham and Stamford","Nick Boles",,"2016-07-14T10:06:21.373Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533554/answer","Biography information for Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533554/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533554/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-07-07","Adult Education","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, how many adult learners paid for courses in each year since 2011.","false","Biography information for Jim McMahon","Oldham West and Royton","Jim McMahon","42195"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533555","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-07-20","<p>As my right hon. Friend the Prime Minister has made clear, while the UK remains a member of the EU, current EU funding and collaboration arrangements continue unchanged, including those that apply to students, researchers, and businesses. I am in close contact with Commissioner Moedas on the topic of Horizon 2020 funding, and I met with the Italian Minister for Education, Universities and Research on 11 July.</p><p>The UK is world-class in research and innovation and we play a leading role in major European and international collaboration, including ESA and CERN.</p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson","42184 ; 42202","2016-07-20T14:47:38.66Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533555/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533555/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533555/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-07-07","Research","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what assessment he has made of the immediate effect of the vote to leave the EU on UK research (a) in general and (b) funding.","false","Biography information for Daniel Zeichner","Cambridge","Daniel Zeichner","42196"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533556","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-07-12","<p>An impact note on the apprenticeship levy is available online: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/apprenticeship-levy/apprenticeship-levy" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/apprenticeship-levy/apprenticeship-levy</a>.</p><p> </p><p>The levy will apply to all employers in all sectors with a paybill above £3million with no exceptions.</p><p> </p><p>The Government will support all employers in using the levy funds to invest in apprenticeships and the Department for Business Innovation and Skills is working with employers to create apprenticeships across all sectors.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Grantham and Stamford","Nick Boles",,"2016-07-12T10:35:38.9Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533556/answer","Biography information for Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533556/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533556/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-07-07","Apprentices: Taxation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what assessment he has made of the effect of the Apprenticeship Levy on the (a) changes made by and (b) finances of employment businesses that supply temporary workers.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","42208"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533557","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-07-12","<p>The Department’s consideration of alternative options is set out in ‘Consultation Response - Proposal for a Combined Headquarters and Policy Centre in London dated Thursday, 26 May, 2016.’</p><p> </p><p>This document was shared with BIS staff and the Departmental Trade Unions. I refer the hon Member to my response to question UIN <a href="http://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-question/Commons/2016-06-07/39823/" target="_blank">39823</a>, which explains why the Department will not be publishing the document; the same reasoning would apply to placing a copy in the Library.</p><p> </p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2016-07-12T16:38:00.82Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533557/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533557/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533557/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-07-07","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills: Reorganisation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, pursuant to the Answer of 6 July 2016 to Question 39599, on Department for Business, Innovation and Skills: reorganisation, if he will place in the Library a copy of any document detailing the assessment that was made of the merits of split-site working and recruiting on a flexible basis through the consideration of alternative options.","false","Biography information for Paul Blomfield","Sheffield Central","Paul Blomfield","42209"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533558","Cabinet Office","false","2016-07-12","<p>The new Europe Unit will bring together officials with a wide range of policy expertise from across Government. Many interest groups have directly approached Government Ministers, and Departments will look to ensure stakeholders’ views are properly captured and considered.</p>","West Dorset","Mr Oliver Letwin",,"2016-07-12T14:09:36.793Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533558/answer","Biography information for Sir Oliver Letwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533558/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533558/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-07-07","Cabinet Office EU Unit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, whether he plans for the EU Unit to include voluntary sector representation or request input from that sector.","false","Biography information for Mary Glindon","North Tyneside","Mary Glindon","42138"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533560","HM Treasury","false","2016-07-12","<p>The Government is committed to the UK hosting the world’s most competitive international financial centre and securing a long-term economic relationship with the rest of Europe that provides for the best possible terms of trade in goods and services, including financial services.</p><p> </p><p>The Chancellor and other Treasury ministers have met, and will continue to meet, a number of financial services stakeholders since the referendum. The impact of the referendum on the financial services industry was discussed at these meetings. Future employment in the UK financial services industry will be commercial decisions for individual firms.</p><p> </p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2016-07-12T16:56:34.827Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533560/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533560/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533560/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-07-07","Financial Services: Employment","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what recent discussions he has had with stakeholders on the implication of the outcome of the EU referendum for future levels of employment in the UK financial services industry.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","42117"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533561","HM Treasury","false","2016-07-12","<p>Each year HM Revenue and Customs (HMRC) receives and responds to 50 million phone calls and 15 million letters from Self Assessment and PAYE customers. HMRC commits to responding to complaints within 15 days of receipt and therefore expects that, excluding any that may be received in the last few weeks before abolition, outstanding complaints will have been cleared.</p><p> </p><p>The number of complaints relating to Class 2 contributions received in the last three years is set out in the table below:</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Year</p></td><td><p>No. of complaints</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013/14</p></td><td><p>1122</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014/15</p></td><td><p>1210</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015/16</p></td><td><p>831</p></td></tr></tbody></table>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2016-07-12T16:41:12.397Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533561/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533561/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533561/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-07-07","National Insurance Contributions: Complaints","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how many complaints relating to class 2 national insurance contributions have been received by HM Revenue and Customs in each of the last three years.","false","Biography information for Mr David Nuttall","Bury North","Mr David Nuttall","42163"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533562","HM Treasury","false","2016-07-12","<p>Each year HM Revenue and Customs (HMRC) receives and responds to 50 million phone calls and 15 million letters from Self Assessment and PAYE customers. HMRC commits to responding to complaints within 15 days of receipt and therefore expects that, excluding any that may be received in the last few weeks before abolition, outstanding complaints will have been cleared.</p><p> </p><p>The number of complaints relating to Class 2 contributions received in the last three years is set out in the table below:</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Year</p></td><td><p>No. of complaints</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013/14</p></td><td><p>1122</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014/15</p></td><td><p>1210</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015/16</p></td><td><p>831</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2016-07-12T16:40:14.173Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533562/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533562/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533562/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-07-07","National Insurance Contributions: Complaints","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what steps he is taking to ensure that all outstanding complaints relating to class 2 national insurance contributions are resolved before those contributions are abolished.","false","Biography information for Mr David Nuttall","Bury North","Mr David Nuttall","42162"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533563","HM Treasury","false","2016-07-13","<p>This level of detail is not requested on VAT returns and therefore we do not have data available on how much revenue is raised from VAT receipts in Greater Manchester.</p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2016-07-13T09:47:14.903Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533563/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533563/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533563/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-07-07","VAT: Greater Manchester","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how much was generated from VAT receipts in Greater Manchester in the last year for which information is available.","false","Biography information for Jim McMahon","Oldham West and Royton","Jim McMahon","42157"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533564","HM Treasury","false","2016-07-12","<p>For part a) estimates of income tax liabilities in respect of Birmingham are included in National Statistics Table 3.14 ('Income and tax by borough and district or unitary authority'), published annually. These estimates are based on the Survey of Personal Incomes for which 2013-14 is the latest tax year available. Figures for the 2008-09 tax year are not currently available.</p><p> </p><p>Table 3.14 for each tax year can be found at the following two links:</p><p>Tables for 1999-2000 to 2009-10, inclusive (except 2008-09, which is not currently available): <a href="http://webarchive.nationalarchives.gov.uk/20120609145917/http:/hmrc.gov.uk/stats/income_distribution/menu-by-year.htm%23313" target="_blank">http://webarchive.nationalarchives.gov.uk/20120609145917/http:/hmrc.gov.uk/stats/income_distribution/menu-by-year.htm#313</a></p><p>Tables for 2010-11 onwards:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/income-and-tax-by-borough-and-district-or-unitary-authority-2010-to-2011" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/income-and-tax-by-borough-and-district-or-unitary-authority-2010-to-2011</a></p><p> </p><p>For part b) The Office for National Statistics Annual Survey of Hours and Earnings (ASHE), is carried out in April each year and is the most comprehensive source of earnings information in the United Kingdom.</p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2016-07-12T16:32:47.217Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533564/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533564/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533564/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-07-07","Pay: Birmingham","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what change there has been in the level of (a) income tax receipts from and (b) average wages in Birmingham over the last 10 years; and what steps he has taken to support the creation of high-quality and high-paying jobs in cities.","false","Biography information for Steve McCabe","Birmingham, Selly Oak","Steve McCabe","42179"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533565","HM Treasury","false","2016-07-13","<p>Work is the best route out of poverty, which is why this Government is focused on getting people into employment. Since 2010, 2.5 million more people are in work and average household incomes are at a record high.</p><p> </p><p>We are reforming the tax and benefit system to ensure work will always pay more than a life on benefits. That is why we are raising the tax-free personal allowance to £11,500 in April 2017, meaning 1.3m individuals will have been taken out of income tax altogether since 2015. This enables people to keep more of what they earn. We are also introducing Universal Credit which is designed to reduce poverty, ensure work pays and strengthen incentives to progress in work.</p><p> </p><p>We have introduced the National Living Wage for workers aged 25 and above, representing a pay rise of £900 this year for a full time workers on the minimum wage.</p><p> </p><p>The Government is also providing additional support for families by increasing childcare funding within UC from 70% to 85% of eligible costs, introducing Tax Free Childcare and extending free early years childcare for working parents from 15 to 30 hours.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2016-07-13T09:00:20.407Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533565/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533565/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533565/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-07-07","Poverty","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what steps he plans to take to reduce in-work poverty.","false","Biography information for Judith Cummins","Bradford South","Judith Cummins","42160"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533566","HM Treasury","false","2016-07-12","<p>The funding for each of Treasury’s sub divisions since 2009-10 can be found on the Main Estimates at www.gov.uk/government/collections/hmt-main-estimates.</p><p> </p><p>The Treasury does not usually set detailed budgets more than a year ahead but have provided the Office for Budget Responsibility with a funding commitment for the period to 2020-21. This can be found at www.budgetresponsibility.org.uk/topics/governance-and-reporting/#letters.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2016-07-12T13:57:30.793Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533566/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533566/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533566/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-07-07","Treasury: Public Expenditure","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what funding was allocated to each of his Department's sub-divisions in each year since 2009-10; and what forecasts of allocations have been made for future years.","false","Biography information for Tulip Siddiq","Hampstead and Kilburn","Tulip Siddiq","42174"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533567","HM Treasury","false","2016-07-12","<p>The teams within each of the five HM Revenue and Customs’ business areas are in the table attached..</p><p> </p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2016-07-12T16:47:16.687Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533567/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533567/answer","Line of Business.docx","Line of Business.docx","PQ attachment","PQ attachment","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533567/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-07-07","Revenue and Customs","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, with reference to the Answer of 12 May 2016 to Question 36723 on Revenue and Customs, if he will list all the teams within each of the five HM Revenue and Customs' business areas.","false","Biography information for Tulip Siddiq","Hampstead and Kilburn","Tulip Siddiq","42175"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533568","HM Treasury","false","2016-07-12","<p>HM Revenue and Customs (HMRC) published its latest tax gap estimates on 22 October 2015 in Measuring tax gaps 2015 edition and is available here: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/measuring-tax-gaps" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/measuring-tax-gaps</a>. A Methodological Annex was also published on the same date.</p><p> </p><p>In Measuring tax gaps 2015 page 65 sets out the definitions of risks. Risks are classified into two broad categories; avoidance and technical risks. The avoidance category relates to the use of disclosed avoidance schemes and other suspected avoidance identified by our tax specialists. Technical risks cover a wide range of risks: from cases where there is genuine uncertainty about the correct tax treatment, through mistakes to culpable errors in, or omissions from, the company tax return.</p><p> </p><p>Avoidance and technical risks are split into four main categories according to how the risks are worked by HMRC (Methodological annex page 59):</p><p>a) Technical risks where agreement has been reached</p><p>b) Technical risks where agreement is expected</p><p>c) Avoidance risks where the enquiry is closed or the risk is being worked</p><p>d) Technical risks that have been litigated or are leading to litigation.</p><p> </p><p>Enforcement options to recover money identified from technical risks not subject to litigation are treated the same as any other non-compliance. The enforcement actions HMRC can take to get any tax owed are published on the gov.uk website <a href="https://www.gov.uk/if-you-dont-pay-your-tax-bill" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/if-you-dont-pay-your-tax-bill</a>.</p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2016-07-12T16:29:09.317Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533568/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533568/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533568/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-07-07","Tax Collection","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, with reference to table 7.1 of HM Revenue and Customs' document, Measuring Tax Gaps, 2015 Edition, published in October 2015, what definition his Department uses of the terms (a) technical risks not subject to litigation, (b) avoidance risks subject to litigation and (c) technical risks subject to litigation; and what enforcement options are available to recover money identified from technical risks not subject to litigation.","false","Biography information for Tulip Siddiq","Hampstead and Kilburn","Tulip Siddiq","42176"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533569","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-07-12","<p>One person without a home is one too many, that is why the Government is clear that prevention must be at the heart of everything we do to tackle homelessness. We have protected homelessness prevention funding for local authorities, which will amount to £315 million by 2020, to help them provide quality advice and assistance to everyone who approaches them for help. We are also exploring options, including legislation, to prevent more people from becoming homeless in the first place.</p><p>And we have also increased central investment to tackle homelessness over the next four years to £139 million, including to fund a £10 million Social Impact Bond to support rough sleepers with the most complex needs. We also announced at Budget £100 million of funding for low-cost move-on accommodation, including for rough sleepers leaving hostels.</p><p> </p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2016-07-12T15:02:12.627Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533569/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533569/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533569/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-07-07","Homelessness: Single People","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what steps his Department is taking to ensure that local authorities provide adequate support to single people who are at risk of homelessness.","false","Biography information for Tim Farron","Westmorland and Lonsdale","Tim Farron","42168"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533570","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-07-13","<p>The Government has implemented a basic broadband scheme to enable all premises to gain access to speeds of at least 2Mbps. This enables residents to gain access to every Government service available online. Funding for subsidised connections through the scheme is provided by Broadband Delivery UK (BDUK) as part of the government's superfast broadband programme. Consumers in eligible premises can access services from any of the suppliers who have been entered onto the scheme by BDUK.</p><p /> <p>In addition it is the Government's intention to implement a new broadband Universal Service Obligation. This will give people the legal right to request a broadband connection, no matter where they live, by the end of this Parliament. Our ambition is that this should initially be set at 10 Mbps.<br></p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2016-07-13T09:23:57.983Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533570/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533570/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533570/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-07-07","Broadband: South Gloucestershire","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, if he will provide details of what additional (a) support and (b) resources his Department is providing to assist South Gloucestershire Council in meeting its universal broadband obligations.","false","Biography information for Luke Hall","Thornbury and Yate","Luke Hall","42165"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533571","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-07-12","<p>As previously stated in the House of Commons, Government is reviewing the situation and I hope to announce details of a review in due course.</p>","Chatham and Aylesford","Tracey Crouch",,"2016-07-12T15:01:21.163Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533571/answer","Biography information for Tracey Crouch","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533571/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533571/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-07-07","Gaming Machines","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, when his Department plans to commence the Triennial Review of Sales and Prizes.","false","Biography information for Dr Tania Mathias","Twickenham","Dr Tania Mathias","42170"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533572","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-07-13","<p>Arts and culture has a hugely positive impact on people's lives and we are committed to broadening access to the arts across the whole country.</p><p> </p><p>Arts Council England are increasing the percentage of Lottery funding distributed outside London from 70 per cent to 75 per cent including over £30 million from their Ambition for Excellence fund that will be spent outside of the capital.</p><p> </p><p>Our Culture White Paper - the first strategy for the sector in more than 50 years - sets out how we will increase access across the country and ensure arts and culture are open to all.</p><p> </p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2016-07-13T15:22:02.253Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533572/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533572/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533572/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-07-07","Arts: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what steps he plans to take to reduce disparities in spending on culture and the arts between London and cities in the North of England.","false","Biography information for Judith Cummins","Bradford South","Judith Cummins","42167"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533573","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-07-13","<p>There are no plans to invest in the infrastructure of Failsworth Army Reserve Centre beyond routine maintenance and running costs.</p><p> </p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster",,"2016-07-13T15:17:19.773Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533573/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533573/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533573/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-07-07","Army Reserve: Greater Manchester","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what plans his Department has to invest in the Failsworth TA Centre.","false","Biography information for Jim McMahon","Oldham West and Royton","Jim McMahon","42194"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533574","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-07-14","<p>The UK has trained female soldiers from the Iraqi Security Forces in infantry skills, combat first aid and explosive hazard awareness as part of the wider Coalition programme to build security force capacity in Iraq. As my right hon. Friend the Secretary of State for Defence announced to the House on 2 September 2014 (Column 16WS), the UK has also gifted non-lethal equipment to the Peshmerga including enhanced combat body armour suitable for both men and women.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2016-07-14T15:32:34.747Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533574/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533574/answer","Hansard Extract 2 September 2014 , (Col 16WS).docx","Hansard Extract 2 September 2014 , (Col 16WS).docx","Operations in Iraq (Update)","Operations in Iraq (Update)","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533574/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-07-07","Iraq: Military Aid","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what support his Department is giving to women soldiers in Iraq through (a) training and (b) provision of body armour.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","42120"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533575","Department for Education","false","2016-07-26","<p>The teaching blog has received an average of 758 visits per week, and 15,938 visits in total. The costs are only in staff time and image usage of £2.50 per image as the blog is hosted on the GOV.UK platform. The blog is run by the Department’s social media team as a small proportion of one member of staff’s overall workload.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb","42149 ; 42151","2016-07-26T08:13:45.85Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533575/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533575/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533575/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-07-07","Teachers: Internet","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how many visits her Department's teaching blog has received on average each week since that blog was established.","false","Biography information for Jess Phillips","Birmingham, Yardley","Jess Phillips","42150"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533576","Department for Education","false","2016-07-14","<p>Local authorities receive funding for early years places through the Dedicated Schools Grant and are responsible for deciding how best to distribute this funding. They are required to fund all early years providers, including free schools with nursery provision, who meet the quality requirements set out in statutory guidance. The department does not keep a central list of the early years providers that are funded by local authorities.</p><p> </p>","Crewe and Nantwich","Edward Timpson",,"2016-07-14T09:33:30.893Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533576/answer","Biography information for Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533576/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533576/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-07-07","Free Schools","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how many free schools offer nursery provision that delivers 15 hours free childcare.","false","Biography information for Jess Phillips","Birmingham, Yardley","Jess Phillips","42152"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533577","Department for Education","false","2016-07-13","<p>The Department for Education received 69 Local Authority applications for the delivery of the three and four year old extended entitlement, a year earlier than planned. These applications were developed in partnership with childcare providers, as part of a formal Expressions of Interest process, which included a rigorous assessment process based on a selection criteria agreed by the Ministerial-level Childcare Implementation Task Force.</p><p> </p><p>The requested information can also be found at:</p><p><a href="https://hansard.parliament.uk/Commons/2016-02-02/debates/16020246000010/ChildcareBillEarlyImplementation?highlight=30%20hours%20free%20childcare#contribution-16020246000032" target="_blank">https://hansard.parliament.uk/Commons/2016-02-02/debates/16020246000010/ChildcareBillEarlyImplementation?highlight=30%20hours%20free%20childcare#contribution-16020246000032</a></p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2016-07-13T12:22:02.157Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533577/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533577/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533577/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-07-07","Children: Day Care","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how many bids her Department received from local authorities to the competition to offer 30 hours free childcare from September 2016.","false","Biography information for Jess Phillips","Birmingham, Yardley","Jess Phillips","42153"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533578","Department for Education","false","2016-07-26","<p>The teaching blog has received an average of 758 visits per week, and 15,938 visits in total. The costs are only in staff time and image usage of £2.50 per image as the blog is hosted on the GOV.UK platform. The blog is run by the Department’s social media team as a small proportion of one member of staff’s overall workload.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb","42150 ; 42151","2016-07-26T08:13:43.227Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533578/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533578/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533578/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-07-07","Teachers: Internet","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how much her Department has spent on its teaching blog since that blog was established.","false","Biography information for Jess Phillips","Birmingham, Yardley","Jess Phillips","42149"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533579","Department for Education","false","2016-07-26","<p>The teaching blog has received an average of 758 visits per week, and 15,938 visits in total. The costs are only in staff time and image usage of £2.50 per image as the blog is hosted on the GOV.UK platform. The blog is run by the Department’s social media team as a small proportion of one member of staff’s overall workload.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb","42149 ; 42150","2016-07-26T08:13:45.927Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533579/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533579/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533579/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-07-07","Teachers: Internet","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how many staff of her Department work on its teaching blog.","false","Biography information for Jess Phillips","Birmingham, Yardley","Jess Phillips","42151"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533580","Department for Education","false","2016-07-14","<p>As with all free schools, Collective Spirit received a project development grant before the school was open and a post-opening grant after the school had opened. The details of these grants are published on GOV.UK: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/revenue-expenditure-for-free-schools" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/revenue-expenditure-for-free-schools</a></p><p>Since the school opened in 2013, the revenue funding of the school has been on a per-pupil basis equivalent to other schools in the local authority area.</p><p>We are currently in the process of confirming both the site acquisition and construction costs for this school. Costs will be published in due course on GOV.UK at: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/capital-funding-for-open-free-schools" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/capital-funding-for-open-free-schools</a></p>","Crewe and Nantwich","Edward Timpson",,"2016-07-14T09:35:03.83Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533580/answer","Biography information for Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533580/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533580/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-07-07","Collective Spirit Free School Oldham","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what (a) funding, (b) land, (c) property and (d) other investment her Department has provided to the Collective Spirit Free School in Oldham.","false","Biography information for Jim McMahon","Oldham West and Royton","Jim McMahon","42166"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533581","Department for Education","false","2016-07-14","<p>Underperformance at any school is unacceptable. The Regional Schools Commissioner, Vicky Beer, has requested an action plan from the trust and will be working with them to identify appropriate and sustained improvements.</p><p>If the trust’s plans fail to convince the department that they are able to make the necessary improvements, we will not hesitate to consider more formal intervention.</p>","Crewe and Nantwich","Edward Timpson",,"2016-07-14T09:33:09.507Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533581/answer","Biography information for Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533581/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533581/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-07-07","Collective Spirit Free School Oldham","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what improvement plan is in place for the Collective Spirit Free School in Oldham.","false","Biography information for Jim McMahon","Oldham West and Royton","Jim McMahon","42159"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533582","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2016-07-12","<p>In the case of gas, UK Trade and Investment is active in helping the UK oil and gas sector do more business internationally. In addition the remit of the new Oil &amp; Gas Authority, established in 2015, is to work with government and industry to make sure that maximum economic benefit is derived from the UK’s oil and gas reserves.</p><p> </p><p>UK companies are freely able to export and import coal as part of normal market operators.</p><p> </p><p>UK demand for both coal and gas outweighs domestic supply, therefore the UK imports the vast majority of its coal needs and around half of its gas supply.</p><p> </p>","Hastings and Rye","Amber Rudd",,"2016-07-12T16:33:40.433Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533582/answer","Biography information for Amber Rudd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533582/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533582/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2016-07-07","Energy: Exports","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, pursuant to the Answer of 28 June 2016 to Question 41415, what assistance the Government provides for UK coal and gas producers seeking to export their fuels overseas to the (a) EU and (b) rest of the world.","false","Biography information for Alan Brown","Kilmarnock and Loudoun","Alan Brown","42143"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533583","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-07-12","<p>Following a public consultation, the following changes to licensing conditions were published on 17 December 2015:</p><p> </p><ul><li><p>Enabling Natural England to keep the duration of annual badger control operations under review rather than limiting them to six weeks.</p><p> </p></li><li><p>Reducing the minimum size of an area from 150km<sup>2 </sup>to 100km<sup>2</sup>.</p><p> </p></li><li><p>Removing the requirement for at least 70% of the land in candidate areas to be accessible but retaining a requirement that approximately 90% of the land in the control area be either accessible, or within 200m of accessible land.</p><p> </p></li></ul>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2016-07-12T15:32:13.79Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533583/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533583/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533583/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-07-07","Bovine Tuberculosis","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what recent changes her Department has made to licensing criteria for badger control in England.","false","Biography information for David Simpson","Upper Bann","David Simpson","42129"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533584","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-07-13","<p>Bovine TB policy is a devolved matter. The UK Chief Veterinary Office and other Defra officials have regular discussions with their counterparts in Northern Ireland on the eradication of bovine TB.</p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2016-07-13T11:30:43.073Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533584/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533584/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533584/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-07-07","Bovine Tuberculosis: Northern Ireland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what discussions she has had with her Northern Ireland counterpart on control of bovine TB in Northern Ireland.","false","Biography information for David Simpson","Upper Bann","David Simpson","42130"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533585","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-07-13","<p>There has been one confirmed case of notifiable avian influenza in poultry during 2016 to date; Low Pathogenic H5N1 at a poultry farm near Dunfermline, Scotland.</p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2016-07-13T11:56:08.257Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533585/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533585/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533585/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-07-07","Avian Influenza","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, how many cases of avian influenza there were in the UK in 2016.","false","Biography information for David Simpson","Upper Bann","David Simpson","42131"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533586","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-07-14","<p>I have regular discussions with the Rural Payments Agency on the progress of Basic Payment Scheme payments.</p><p>As of 3 July 86,760 (99.6%) farmers have received a payment on their 2015 BPS claim. The Rural Payments Agency continues to focus on making top up payments to those farmers who have already received a bridging payment.</p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2016-07-14T10:57:20.577Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533586/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533586/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533586/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-07-07","Agriculture: Subsidies","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what recent discussions she has had with the Rural Payments Agency to resolve the backlog of 2015 Basic Payment Scheme payments.","false","Biography information for David Simpson","Upper Bann","David Simpson","42132"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533587","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-07-13","<p>For the Basic Payment Scheme 2016 over 80% of farmers chose to apply online.</p><p> </p><p>For the Basic Payment Scheme 2017 the Rural Payments Agency will have a planned campaign of activity to encourage as many as possible of the remaining 20% of customers that applied on paper to apply online.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2016-07-13T11:59:06.567Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533587/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533587/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533587/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-07-07","Agriculture: Subsidies","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, how her Department plans to encourage more farmers to submit their Basic Payment Scheme payments applications online.","false","Biography information for David Simpson","Upper Bann","David Simpson","42133"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533588","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-07-13","<p>Defra uses both monitoring and modelling to assess air quality in the UK. The Department has five monitoring stations in the Greater Manchester Urban Agglomeration, at: Bury Whitefield Roadside, Manchester Piccadilly, Manchester Sharston, Salford Eccles and Shaw Crompton Way. Information about the sites and the pollutants measured is available on Defra’s UK-Air website.</p><p> </p><p>Nitrogen dioxide pollution from road transport is the predominant source of air pollution in the Greater Manchester area.</p><p> </p><p>There have been two measured exceedances of the annual mean air pollution objective for nitrogen dioxide in the Greater Manchester Urban Agglomeration since 2011. These were recorded in the Bury Whitefield Roadside and Manchester Piccadilly monitoring sites in 2011 and 2012. However, based on both modelling and monitoring carried out for compliance purposes, the zone was reported to have exceeded the annual mean limit value for nitrogen dioxide for all years between 2011 and 2014.</p><p> </p><p>Local authorities have a crucial role to play in improving air quality in their areas. They are required to review and assess air quality in their areas and to designate Air Quality Management Areas (AQMAs) and put in place Air Quality Action Plans (AQAPs) to address air pollution issues where national air quality objectives are not being met.</p><p> </p><p>The ten local authorities in the Greater Manchester area designated AQMAs between 2001 and 2007. In 2016 the Greater Manchester Combined Authority (GMCA) amalgamated all AQMAs across the region into a single AQMA. The GMCA has put in place an AQAP that sets out measures aimed at promoting sustainable transport initiatives, including proposals to introduce Ultra-Low Emission Zones.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2016-07-13T11:33:40.297Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533588/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533588/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533588/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-07-07","Air Pollution: Greater Manchester","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, how many times air quality safety levels were breached in Greater Manchester in each year since 2011.","false","Biography information for Jim McMahon","Oldham West and Royton","Jim McMahon","42158"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533589","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-07-12","<p>Following the result of the EU Referendum, we now have an opportunity to consider our long term vision for food and farming outside of the EU.</p><p> </p><p>It remains essential that the UK has a thriving food and farming industry with high animal welfare and environmental standards, access to international markets and a long term commitment to boosting productivity through innovation and skills. We are now focused on taking forward the actions that support these objectives, in order to develop our long term vision. To do this, we will continue to work with a wide range of interests to develop that vision, and to work together to deliver it.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice","42231","2016-07-12T16:56:46.33Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533589/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533589/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533589/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-07-07","Agriculture","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, whether her Department has amended its draft of the 25 year plan on food and farming as a result of the outcome of the EU referendum.","false","Biography information for Kerry McCarthy","Bristol East","Kerry McCarthy","42145"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533590","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-07-14","<p>The Secretary of State is writing to the Minister of Agriculture, Environment and Rural Affairs in Northern Ireland to outline the steps we are taking to help our hard-pressed dairy farmers. These include: securing a £26.2 million aid package from the European Commission, introducing a new system of extended tax averaging, and working with the Treasury to assess whether improved access to risk management tools can contribute to the resilience of the dairy industry.</p><p> </p><p>I regularly meet representatives of the dairy industry from across the UK, including from Northern Ireland, to discuss issues of mutual interest and Defra officials maintain regular contact with their counterparts in the devolved administrations on a range of dairy issues.</p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2016-07-14T11:07:13.703Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533590/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533590/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533590/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-07-07","Dairy Farming: Northern Ireland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what discussions she has had with her Northern Ireland counterparts on assistance for dairy farmers in Northern Ireland; and what assistance her Department is giving such farmers.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","42197"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533591","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-07-13","<p>2015 has been a challenging year for a number of well documented reasons. We understand the importance of Basic Payment Scheme (BPS) payments for farmers and their particular frustration in the first year of this new scheme.</p><p> </p><p>From 1 December 2015, the Rural Payments Agency (RPA) made full and accurate 2015 BPS payments which continued throughout the payment window. As of 3 July, some 85,852 (98.6%) of 2015 BPS claims have now been completed and 86,760 have received a payment amounting to some £1.3billion.</p><p> </p><p>The RPA remain focused on making full and accurate payments as promptly as possible. They are also committed to improving payment performance in 2016, and 2016 should be easier as we will have both the systems and data already in place. Ministers have regular meetings with the RPA and closely monitor its performance.</p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2016-07-13T16:09:59.633Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533591/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533591/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533591/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-07-07","Agriculture: Subsidies","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what assessment she has made of the potential merits of imposing fines on the Rural Payments Agency for late Basic Payment Scheme payments to farmers.","false","Biography information for Scott Mann","North Cornwall","Scott Mann","42188"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533592","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-07-13","<p>The UK has been working through the Convention on International Trade in Endangered Species (CITES) to tighten controls ensuring that trophies of endangered species are only exported if the animals were hunted sustainably.</p><p> </p><p>CITES import controls are currently implemented at an EU-wide level. In light of growing concerns about the sustainability of the hunting of some species, stricter controls on the import of hunting trophies of six species, including lions and African elephants, have been introduced. On the advice of EU CITES scientific experts, Member States also prohibit the importation of a number of species from certain countries where there is uncertainty about sustainability, such as elephant hunting trophies from Mozambique and Tanzania.</p><p> </p><p>We continue to monitor the impact of trophy hunting and will work to put in place greater protection, including prohibiting imports, if this is shown to be needed. For example, I announced on 24 November 2015 that the Government will ban lion trophy imports by the end of 2017 unless there are improvements in the way hunting takes place in certain countries, judged against strict criteria.</p><p> </p><p>The UK is also pushing for tougher hunting trophy controls to be agreed at the 17th Conference of Parties to CITES in the autumn. A UK-led EU proposal aims to agree global guidelines to ensure that hunting trophy exports are sustainable, and agree clear criteria on when lion trophy hunting can be considered acceptable.</p><p> </p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2016-07-13T11:41:09.44Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533592/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533592/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533592/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-07-07","Hunting","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what steps she is taking to help prevent the hunting to extinction of endangered species.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","42211"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533593","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-07-14","<p>The National Air Quality Plan for nitrogen dioxide, published in December last year, sets out a comprehensive approach for meeting the air quality challenges by implementing a new programme of Clean Air Zones, along with the Ultra-Low Emission Zone in London. The Plan combines targeted local and national measures, forming part of a wider approach that exploits new and clean technologies, such as electric and ultra-low emission vehicles.</p><p> </p><p>The Government has committed over £2 billion since 2011 to increase the uptake of ultra-low emission vehicles, support green transport initiatives and support local authorities to take action.</p><p> </p><p>The Mayor is responsible for air quality standards in London. The Mayor provides the framework and guidance which London boroughs use to review and improve air quality within their areas. The new Mayor recently set out his plans to improve air quality in London.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2016-07-14T15:56:55.343Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533593/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533593/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533593/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-07-07","Air Pollution: Greater London","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what steps the Government is taking to work with the Mayor of London to improve air quality in London.","false","Biography information for Neil Coyle","Bermondsey and Old Southwark","Neil Coyle","42204"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533594","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-07-13","<p>Until we leave the EU, current arrangements for farming, fisheries, food and drink and our environment remain in place.</p><p> </p><p>The negotiation for Britain's future relationship with Europe will need to begin under the next Prime Minister.</p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2016-07-13T11:49:36.637Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533594/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533594/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533594/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-07-07","Agriculture: Regulation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what assessment she has made of the potential effect of the UK leaving the EU on the amount of regulation on farming.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","42212"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533595","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-07-12","<p>We strongly condemn the attack against the civilian residents of Camp Liberty in Iraq on 4 July. In all of our engagement with the Government of Iraq on this issue, including at Ministerial level and in our statements, we have emphasised the importance of the Iraqi Government doing everything possible to ensure the safety of the residents of Camp Liberty.</p><p>It is the responsibility of the Government of Iraq to investigate the attack against the camp and to provide adequate protection to the residents. We have publically called on the Government of Iraq to investigate the attack and bring the attackers to justice. In the coming days officials from our Embassy will raise the attack with the Iraqi Prime Minister’s Office and the Ministry of Foreign Affairs and make clear the importance of an urgent and comprehensive investigation into the incident.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2016-07-12T16:34:58.133Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533595/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533595/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533595/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-07-07","Iraq: Iran","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, if he will make it his policy to instigate a prompt and independent inquiry into the (a) missile attack on Camp Liberty on 4 July 2016 and (b) effectiveness of protection of residents of that camp.","false","Biography information for Martyn Day","Linlithgow and East Falkirk","Martyn Day","42173"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533596","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-07-13","The Government is committed to promoting and protecting the right to freedom of religion or belief around the world, and to being a strong voice internationally in defence of this fundamental right. We raise these and other human rights issues with the Vietnamese government regularly and at all levels. We also work with non-government organisations and likeminded embassies on human rights issues in Vietnam. I raised concerns about the general human rights situation in Vietnam with the Vietnamese Deputy Foreign Minister during the UK-Vietnam Strategic Dialogue in London in March 2016. The Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, my Rt Hon. Friend the Member for Runnymede and Weybridge (Mr Hammond), discussed human rights with the Vietnamese Prime Minister during his visit to Vietnam in April 2016. We will continue to raise these issues with the Vietnamese authorities, including a concerning report from Amnesty International which has just issued on the treatment of prisoners of conscience in Vietnam.","East Devon","Mr Hugo Swire",,"2016-07-13T13:51:25.787Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533596/answer","Biography information for Sir Hugo Swire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533596/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533596/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-07-07","Vietnam: Human Rights","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what discussions he has had with the Vietnamese government on human rights abuses and persecution of Christians.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","42119"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533597","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-07-13","<p>Encouraging travellers to obtain comprehensive travel insurance is a key part of the Foreign and Commonwealth Office’s ‘Travel Aware’ communications campaign, which has been active since 2001 (formerly known as Know Before You Go). Messaging on insurance is prominent in many of our travel safety materials and we run specific campaigns on insurance, reaching the travelling public through media engagement, digital activity and collaboration with industry partners such as ABTA and the Association of British Insurers.</p><p>We have worked with the Association of British Insurers to create a new ‘checklist’ to help travellers choose the right insurance policy for their needs, which we communicate through social media and our network of industry partners. Our messages on insurance have also been reinforced by broadcasts on a wide range of national, regional and community TV and radio stations.</p>","Rochford and Southend East","James Duddridge",,"2016-07-13T12:47:15.06Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533597/answer","Biography information for James Duddridge","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533597/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533597/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-07-07","Travel: Insurance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what steps his Department is taking to encourage UK travellers abroad to take out adequate holiday insurance.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","42121"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533598","Department of Health","false","2016-07-13","<p>The Department has not conducted or commissioned specific research on this topic.</p><p> </p><p>The Department’s National Institute for Health Research (NIHR) is investing £4.5 million over five years in the NIHR Bristol Nutrition Biomedical Research Unit (BRU). This BRU aims to translate knowledge developed from work on causal associations in nutrition, drawn from population and clinical studies, to develop interventions that improve the health of people with conditions related to poor nutrition. One of the BRU’s research areas is prostate cancer. The overall aim of work in this area is to investigate the feasibility of undertaking randomised controlled trials of nutritional and physical activity interventions in men with prostate cancer and the impact of these interventions on cancer pathology to identify promising interventions to develop into phase III tertiary prevention trials.</p>","Mid Norfolk","George Freeman",,"2016-07-13T15:15:50.673Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533598/answer","Biography information for George Freeman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533598/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533598/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-07-07","Cancer: Mortality Rates","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what research his Department has conducted on the links between cancer survival rates, diet and exercise.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","42123"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533599","Department of Health","false","2016-07-11","<p>Improving Access to Psychological Therapies (IAPT) services treat common mental health conditions, including anxiety. More than 3.5 million adults have entered the IAPT programme since its inception in 2008. Of that 3.5 million, over 2.1 million have completed treatment and over 725,000 are in recovery and more than 100,000 people have moved off sick pay and benefits.</p><p> </p><p>We have introduced waiting times standards to ensure better access to IAPT so that 75% of people referred to IAPT receive treatment within six weeks and 95% receive treatment within 18 weeks.</p><p> </p><p>In January 2016, the Government announced almost £1 billion of additional investment for mental health, which included £290 million of new investment over the next five years to provide mental healthcare for perinatal care.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2016-07-11T15:24:54.47Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533599/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533599/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533599/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-07-07","Anxiety: Females","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what steps he is taking to reduce anxiety disorder in women under 35.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","42124"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533600","Department of Health","false","2016-07-13","<p>The Department has made no assessment of the quality of acute, post and community stroke care in rural and metropolitan areas. However, the Sentinel Stroke National Audit programme reports the results of the quality of both hospital and community care quarterly at trust and clinical commissioning group level. These data are in the public domain and can be found at:</p><p> </p><p><a href="http://www.strokeaudit.org" target="_blank">www.strokeaudit.org</a></p><p> </p><p>NHS England’s <em>Five Year Forward View</em> sets out the healthcare strategy for the whole of England, including rural areas. Rural areas have their own health needs, which should be taken into account in planning and developing healthcare systems. It is for clinical commissioning groups to judge the needs of their local areas and make sure that they are reflecting the specific circumstances of those areas.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison","42146 ; 42148","2016-07-13T17:14:31.643Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533600/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533600/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533600/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-07-07","Strokes","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what comparative assessment he has made of the quality of acute stroke care in rural areas and in metropolitan areas.","false","Biography information for Glyn Davies","Montgomeryshire","Glyn Davies","42147"
