"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533604","Department of Health","false","2016-07-13","<p>The proposed reforms to healthcare education funding for introduction on 1 August 2017 will not require amendments to the legislation under which the National Health Service bursary is provided.</p>","Ipswich","Ben Gummer",,"2016-07-13T13:36:38.233Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533604/answer","Biography information for Ben Gummer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533604/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533604/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-07-07","Health Professions: Training","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, whether legislative changes will be required to remove the NHS bursary for healthcare students by September 2017; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Dr Sarah Wollaston","Totnes","Dr Sarah Wollaston","42161"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533605","Department of Health","false","2016-07-12","<p>Drug and alcohol treatment services in England are funded by local authorities from the public health grant, which does not include European Union funding streams. Individual drug and alcohol treatment services may have applied for and received EU funding, however this data is not collected centrally.</p><p> </p><p>As the Prime Minister has made clear, while the United Kingdom remains a member of the EU, current EU funding arrangements continue unchanged. It will be for the Government under the new Prime Minister to begin the negotiation to leave, and set out arrangements for those schemes currently in receipt of EU funds.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2016-07-12T13:02:26.603Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533605/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533605/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533605/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-07-07","Alcoholic Drinks and Drugs: Misuse","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what assessment his Department has made of the extent to which UK drug and alcohol treatment is dependent on EU funding streams; whether such streams will remain open until such time as Article 50 is enacted; and what measures his Department plans to put in place to maintain the level of that funding from the public purse after Article 50 is enacted.","false","Biography information for Mary Glindon","North Tyneside","Mary Glindon","42140"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533606","Department of Health","false","2016-07-13","<p>The Department has not conducted or commissioned specific research on this topic.</p>","Mid Norfolk","George Freeman",,"2016-07-13T15:23:52.633Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533606/answer","Biography information for George Freeman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533606/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533606/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-07-07","Perinatal Mortality: Air Pollution","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what research his Department has conducted on potential links between rates of stillbirth and exposure to high levels of air pollution.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","42118"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533607","Department of Health","false","2016-07-12","<p>The Government has no plans to require manufacturers to display the calorific contents of alcoholic drinks on labels. However, some businesses do choose to do so voluntarily.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2016-07-12T14:09:01.737Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533607/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533607/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533607/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-07-07","Alcoholic Drinks: Labelling","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what plans he has to require manufacturers to display the calorific content of alcoholic drinks on labels.","false","Biography information for Sir Mark Hendrick","Preston","Mr Mark Hendrick","42171"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533608","Department of Health","false","2016-07-13","<p>We have taken steps to improve the health of Gypsies, Travellers and Roma people as part of our broader social inclusion policies. The inclusion health programme sought to identify and promote good practice across the National Health Service and elsewhere. It has included: developing practical guidance on the commissioning of more inclusive services to help ensure the needs of disadvantaged and vulnerable groups are taken into account in shaping local plans and priorities; working with primary health care professionals and others to improve access to services for these groups; and supporting the education and training of health professionals to enable them to work more effectively with these groups. This work is being carried forward across the health system.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2016-07-13T17:12:18.457Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533608/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533608/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533608/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-07-07","Travellers: Health","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what steps his Department has taken under the National Roma Integration Strategy to enhance the health integration of Gypsy Traveller Roma people.","false","Biography information for Grant Shapps","Welwyn Hatfield","Grant Shapps","42164"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533609","Department of Health","false","2016-07-13","<p>The tables below shows 1) the number of courses of treatment (CoT) for children age 10 and under in Primary Dental Care which included an extraction and 2) the number of Finished Consultant Episodes (FCEs) for children aged 10 and under including an extraction due to tooth decay.</p><p> </p><p>During the same period, the population for children age 10 and under rose from 6.9 million to 7.3 million. The figures suggest the total rise in extractions and therefore increases in health costs are broadly in line with the increase in population of this age group over the same period.</p><p>1)</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Financial year</p></td><td><p>(CoT) Extractions per 100,000</p></td><td><p>Primary Care (CoT)</p></td><td><p>Population</p></td><td><p>change</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014/15</p></td><td><p>3211.0</p></td><td><p>234,704</p></td><td><p>7,309,300</p></td><td><p>-8,274</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013/14</p></td><td><p>3380.7</p></td><td><p>242,978</p></td><td><p>7,187,200</p></td><td><p>9,186</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012/13</p></td><td><p>3317.0</p></td><td><p>233,792</p></td><td><p>7,048,300</p></td><td><p>718</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2011/12</p></td><td><p>3376.9</p></td><td><p>233,074</p></td><td><p>6,902,100</p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr></tbody></table><p><em>Source:</em> NHS Business Services Authority, extract from FP17 form clinical data set information 2011/12 – 2014/15</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>2)</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Financial year</p></td><td><p>FCE Extractions per 100,000</p></td><td><p>FCEs</p></td><td><p>Population</p></td><td><p>change</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014/15</p></td><td><p>462.2</p></td><td><p>33,781</p></td><td><p>7,309,300</p></td><td><p>1040</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013/14</p></td><td><p>455.5</p></td><td><p>32,741</p></td><td><p>7,187,200</p></td><td><p>1466</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012/13</p></td><td><p>443.7</p></td><td><p>31,275</p></td><td><p>7,048,300</p></td><td><p>514</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2011/12</p></td><td><p>445.7</p></td><td><p>30,761</p></td><td><p>6,902,100</p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr></tbody></table><p><em>Source:</em> Health and Social Care Information Centre, Hospital Episode Statistics 2011/12 – 2014/15</p><p> </p><p> </p><p>However, the Government is serious about improving oral health for children. Initiatives to improve oral health include targeted interventions in ten high needs areas and reform of the dental contract to focus on prevention.</p><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p><p><strong> </strong></p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2016-07-13T09:41:59.797Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533609/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533609/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533609/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-07-07","Dental Health: Children","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what assessment his Department has made of the long-term health costs associated with the increase in the number of dental extractions in children under the age of 10 in the last four years.","false","Biography information for Judith Cummins","Bradford South","Judith Cummins","42185"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533610","Department of Health","false","2016-07-12","<p>For the first time, from May 2016, cessation information to signpost consumers to quitting support has become mandatory on tobacco products. The Government’s advice remains that the best thing a smoker can do is to quit and quit for good. Any smokers wanting to quit, with or without the help of products available on the market, are four times more likely to stop smoking and quit for good with the personalised support offered by local stop smoking services.</p><p> </p><p>The National Centre for Stop Smoking Services has issued guidance on offering advice to those wanting to use e-cigarettes as part of their quit attempts and encouraged local stop smoking services to be open to their use.</p><p> </p><p>The Government recognises that some people have found e-cigarettes helpful in quitting smoking and that they are considerably less harmful than continuing to smoke. The forthcoming tobacco control plan will consider the role of e-cigarettes and other harm reduction products in further reducing the prevalence of smoking in England.</p><p> </p><p>The Department has no current plans to review the restrictions on advertising for tobacco products.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison","42181 ; 42183","2016-07-12T14:54:44.71Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533610/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533610/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533610/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-07-07","Tobacco: Advertising","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what plans his Department has to review advertising regulations for reduced-harm tobacco products to take account of the potential of those products to help people quit smoking.","false","Biography information for Paul Farrelly","Newcastle-under-Lyme","Paul Farrelly","42180"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533611","Department of Health","false","2016-07-12","<p>For the first time, from May 2016, cessation information to signpost consumers to quitting support has become mandatory on tobacco products. The Government’s advice remains that the best thing a smoker can do is to quit and quit for good. Any smokers wanting to quit, with or without the help of products available on the market, are four times more likely to stop smoking and quit for good with the personalised support offered by local stop smoking services.</p><p> </p><p>The National Centre for Stop Smoking Services has issued guidance on offering advice to those wanting to use e-cigarettes as part of their quit attempts and encouraged local stop smoking services to be open to their use.</p><p> </p><p>The Government recognises that some people have found e-cigarettes helpful in quitting smoking and that they are considerably less harmful than continuing to smoke. The forthcoming tobacco control plan will consider the role of e-cigarettes and other harm reduction products in further reducing the prevalence of smoking in England.</p><p> </p><p>The Department has no current plans to review the restrictions on advertising for tobacco products.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison","42180 ; 42183","2016-07-12T14:54:44.807Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533611/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533611/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533611/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-07-07","Smoking: Health Education","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what steps his Department is taking to advise smokers on the range of harm-reduction products available to help them quit smoking.","false","Biography information for Paul Farrelly","Newcastle-under-Lyme","Paul Farrelly","42181"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533612","Department of Health","false","2016-07-12","<p>The Department’s Policy Research Programme funds the Public Health Research Consortium (PHRC). The PHRC is undertaking the project ‘E-Cigarettes: Development of Tools to Measure Norms Towards Ordinary Cigarettes and Nicotine Use’. This started in April 2015 and is currently in the write-up stage. It is due to go to peer review and publication plans will be developed subsequently.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison","42210","2016-07-12T14:56:43.547Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533612/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533612/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533612/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-07-07","Electronic Cigarettes","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what recent work his Department has commissioned with the Public Health Research Consortium on the effects of e-cigarettes.","false","Biography information for Paul Farrelly","Newcastle-under-Lyme","Paul Farrelly","42182"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533613","Department of Health","false","2016-07-12","<p>For the first time, from May 2016, cessation information to signpost consumers to quitting support has become mandatory on tobacco products. The Government’s advice remains that the best thing a smoker can do is to quit and quit for good. Any smokers wanting to quit, with or without the help of products available on the market, are four times more likely to stop smoking and quit for good with the personalised support offered by local stop smoking services.</p><p> </p><p>The National Centre for Stop Smoking Services has issued guidance on offering advice to those wanting to use e-cigarettes as part of their quit attempts and encouraged local stop smoking services to be open to their use.</p><p> </p><p>The Government recognises that some people have found e-cigarettes helpful in quitting smoking and that they are considerably less harmful than continuing to smoke. The forthcoming tobacco control plan will consider the role of e-cigarettes and other harm reduction products in further reducing the prevalence of smoking in England.</p><p> </p><p>The Department has no current plans to review the restrictions on advertising for tobacco products.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison","42180 ; 42181","2016-07-12T14:54:44.867Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533613/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533613/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533613/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-07-07","Tobacco","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, whether he plans to include reduced-harm products in the Government's tobacco control plan on account of their potential health benefits to smokers.","false","Biography information for Paul Farrelly","Newcastle-under-Lyme","Paul Farrelly","42183"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533614","Home Office","false","2016-07-13","<p>The final report on the handling of family reunion applications has not yet been sent to the Home Office by the Chief Inspector of Borders and Immigration.</p><p>Arrangements for publication will be considered once the final report has been received</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2016-07-13T13:44:17.64Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533614/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533614/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533614/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-07-07","Asylum: Families","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, when she plans to publish the report by the Chief Inspector of Borders and Immigration on the handling of family reunion applications.","false","Biography information for Caroline Lucas","Brighton, Pavilion","Caroline Lucas","42187"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533615","Home Office","false","2016-07-12","<p>The Government has been clear that there will be no immediate changes in the circumstances of European nationals and their family members entering or currently residing in the UK.</p><p>The Government wants to be able to guarantee the legal status of EU nationals who are living in the UK, and we are confident that we will be able to do this. But we must also win the same rights for British nationals living in European countries, and it will be an early negotiating objective for the Government to achieve those things together.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2016-07-12T14:05:17.057Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533615/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533615/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533615/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-07-07","Migrant Workers: EU Nationals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what assurance her Department plans to give EU nationals living in the UK and working in the voluntary sector on their right to remain in the UK after the EU referendum.","false","Biography information for Mary Glindon","North Tyneside","Mary Glindon","42139"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533616","Department for International Development","false","2016-07-13","<p>Syria is the world’s biggest and most urgent humanitarian crisis. 13.5 million people are in need of humanitarian assistance and four in five Syrians live in poverty. The UN estimates that since the crisis began life expectancy among Syrians has dropped by more than 20 years, from 79.5 years to 55.7 years. Significant contributory factors include death rates due to the conflict (including increased death rates among younger people); destruction of health care facilities and difficulties in delivering routine childhood vaccinations; and an increase in poverty.</p><p>The UK is at the forefront of the response to the crisis. UK support is reaching hundreds of thousands of people affected by it in Syria, Jordan, Lebanon, Turkey, Iraq and Egypt. The UK has pledged over £2.3 billion, our largest ever response to a single humanitarian crisis. We are also mobilising the international community. We co-hosted the “Supporting Syria and the Region” conference in London on 4 February, which secured pledges of more than $12 billion, the largest amount raised in one day for a humanitarian crisis. Of this, over $6 billion was pledged for support in 2016 and a further $6.1 billion for the coming years until 2020. This money will save lives, give hope and give people a chance for the future</p>","New Forest West","Sir Desmond Swayne",,"2016-07-13T12:38:55.68Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533616/answer","Biography information for Sir Desmond Swayne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533616/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533616/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-07-07","Syria: Life Expectancy","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what representations she has received on trends in life expectancy in Syria; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Andrew Stephenson","Pendle","Andrew Stephenson","42191"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533617","Northern Ireland Office","false","2016-07-14","<p>The PSNI will receive Additional Security Funding totalling £160m over this parliament. Over the next 5 years £2.5 billion will also be invested in the Security and Intelligence Agencies to create a bigger more capable global security and intelligence network. This is significant funding. It matches the severity of the terrorist threat, it demonstrates our unwavering commitment to the brave men and women in the police and intelligence agencies, and it is helping to keep people safe.</p><p> </p>","Chipping Barnet","Mrs Theresa Villiers",,"2016-07-14T10:27:55.223Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533617/answer","Biography information for Theresa Villiers","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533617/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533617/answer",,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2016-07-07","Terrorism: Northern Ireland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Northern Ireland, what funding has been provided to tackle terrorism in Northern Ireland under the Strategic Defence and Security Review 2015.","false","Biography information for Nigel Dodds","Belfast North","Mr Nigel Dodds","42190"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533618","Northern Ireland Office","false","2016-07-14","<p>We are making significant progress in the arrangements to establish the Independent Reporting Commission (IRC) by the end of this year. We are working with the Government of Ireland to finalise the detail of the international treaty which will establish the Commission and I propose to bring forward supporting regulations on the appropriate immunities and privileges as soon as possible after the Treaty is signed.</p>","Chipping Barnet","Mrs Theresa Villiers",,"2016-07-14T10:33:14.843Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533618/answer","Biography information for Theresa Villiers","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533618/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533618/answer",,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2016-07-07","Stormont House Agreement","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Northern Ireland, what progress has been made on the establishment of an independent reporting commission under the Fresh Start Agreement.","false","Biography information for Nigel Dodds","Belfast North","Mr Nigel Dodds","42186"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533619","Northern Ireland Office","false","2016-07-14","<p>I attended a Security Interface meeting on 4 July 2016 with Clare Sugden MLA, Minister of Justice for Northern Ireland, representatives of PSNI and senior representatives of the Department of Justice. We received an update on the work of the Joint Agency Task Force. The Task Force has presented its first report to the meeting of Justice Ministers in the framework of the Intergovernmental Agreement on co-operation on criminal justice matters, with an update on operational activity undertaken to date.</p>","Chipping Barnet","Mrs Theresa Villiers",,"2016-07-14T10:22:26.027Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533619/answer","Biography information for Theresa Villiers","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533619/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533619/answer",,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2016-07-07","Cross Border Cooperation: Northern Ireland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Northern Ireland, what recent discussions she has had with the Northern Ireland Executive on the Joint Agency Task Force; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Nigel Dodds","Belfast North","Mr Nigel Dodds","42189"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533620","Cabinet Office","false","2016-07-12","<p>This government will streamline the public bodies landscape through a robust programme of “tailored reviews” overseen by the Cabinet Office and department-led transformation programmes. Non-ministerial departments, non-departmental public bodies and executive agencies will be reviewed once per parliament. These reviews will examine whether their functions should still be delivered at arm’s length, and if so, aim to increase their efficiency, effectiveness, and accountability. This builds on the public bodies reform programme delivered from 2010-15, which successfully produced fewer, more accountable, and more efficient public bodies.</p>","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock",,"2016-07-12T08:27:55.2Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533620/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533620/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533620/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-07-07","Public Bodies","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what steps he is taking to reduce the number of public bodies across government.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","42122"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533621","Department for Transport","false","2016-07-12","<p>At almost every Motorway Service Area in the UK there is at least one rapid electric vehicle chargepoint. A full list of the available chargepoints at Motorway Service Areas can be found on the Government’s National Chargepoint Registry: <a href="http://www.national-charge-point-registry.uk/" target="_blank">http://www.national-charge-point-registry.uk/</a>.</p><p> </p><p>Highways England has a £15 million project to ensure that there is a chargepoint every 20 miles across 95% of the strategic road network, with the aim that these should be rapid chargepoints wherever possible.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2016-07-12T10:15:44.08Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533621/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533621/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533621/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-07-07","Motorway Service Areas: Electric Vehicles","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how many motorway service stations have rapid chargers installed to allow charging of electric vehicles.","false","Biography information for Alan Brown","Kilmarnock and Loudoun","Alan Brown","42144"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533622","Department for Transport","false","2016-07-14","<p>There have not been, and there are, no ‘non-planned’ services.</p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2016-07-14T07:31:35.97Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533622/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533622/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533622/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-07-07","Govia Thameslink Railway: Standards","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what proportion of non-planned Govia Thameslink Railway services were cancelled in each reporting period since July 2015.","false","Biography information for Kelvin Hopkins","Luton North","Kelvin Hopkins","42134"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533623","Department for Transport","false","2016-07-14","<p>The Department did not design either the Remedial Plan, or the revised timetable being introduced on 11 July. Emergency timetables are introduced by the rail industry in reaction to specific circumstances as they are responsible for operating the railway and do not need the prior approval of the Secretary of State.</p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2016-07-14T07:33:40.037Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533623/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533623/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533623/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-07-07","Govia Thameslink Railway: Standards","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, whether external consultants were involved in the design of the (a) Remedial Plan or (b) emergency timetable for Govia Thameslink Railway services.","false","Biography information for Kelvin Hopkins","Luton North","Kelvin Hopkins","42135"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533624","Department for Transport","false","2016-07-14","<p>Emergency timetables are introduced by the rail industry in reaction to specific circumstances as they are responsible for operating the railway and do not need the prior approval of the Secretary of State. GTR has introduced a revised timetable which seeks to use the resources that are likely to be available in order to provide a service that passengers can rely on. It is for the operator, in conjunction with Network Rail, to manage the timetable effectively.</p><p> </p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2016-07-14T07:35:36.627Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533624/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533624/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533624/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-07-07","Govia Thameslink Railway: Standards","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, whether his Department is required to consult (a) passenger groups, (b) trade unions and (c) Network Rail before the introduction of an emergency timetable on Govia Thameslink Railway services can take place.","false","Biography information for Kelvin Hopkins","Luton North","Kelvin Hopkins","42136"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533625","Department for Transport","false","2016-07-14","<p>The successful bidder for the East Anglia franchise will help us realise our ambitious plans for East Anglia’s rail network. We have been clear that as a minimum they must provide a modern service with state of the art trains, and also introduce at least two 90-minute services each way between London and Norwich. In addition they must invest heavily in improving stations.</p><p> </p><p>We continue to consider the bids and will announce the new operator in due course.</p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2016-07-14T07:37:37.007Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533625/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533625/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533625/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-07-07","Railways: East of England","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, when he plans to announce the award of the next franchise for passenger services on the Greater Anglia line.","false","Biography information for Kelvin Hopkins","Luton North","Kelvin Hopkins","42137"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533626","Department for Transport","false","2016-07-12","<p>Highways England’s traffic officer service has 198 vehicles. On a typical weekday, there are approximately 90 vehicles deployed during the day shifts and around 49 for night times. Where there are major events or severe weather warnings, with likely impacts on the strategic road network, additional vehicles will be used.</p><p> </p><p>None of the vehicles carry defibrillators.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2016-07-12T10:26:08.3Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533626/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533626/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533626/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-07-07","Highways England: Vehicles","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how many Highways England vehicles there are available for motorway patrol; how many such vehicles are deployed at any one time; and how many such vehicles deployed carry defibrillators.","false","Biography information for Robert Flello","Stoke-on-Trent South","Robert Flello","42141"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533627","Department for Transport","false","2016-07-12","<p>Later this year the rail industry will present its initial advice to Government on investment needs for the national network, drawing on the outputs of Network Rail’s long term planning process, including its refresh of the national electrification strategy. Taking account of this advice and other inputs – including from Transport for the North - the Government intends to articulate its emerging priorities for improvement to the national network during 2017.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2016-07-12T10:06:48.3Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533627/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533627/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533627/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-07-07","Calder Valley Railway Line: Electrification","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what assessment he has made of the potential economic benefits to Bradford and the wider regional economy of electrifying the Calder Valley line.","false","Biography information for Judith Cummins","Bradford South","Judith Cummins","42155"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533628","Department for Transport","false","2016-07-13","<p>The Driver and Vehicle Licensing Agency does not hold information on the amount of vehicle excise duty revenue collected by geographical region. The total vehicle excise duty revenue collected in financial year 2014-15 was around £6 billion.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2016-07-13T08:47:21.033Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533628/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533628/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533628/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-07-07","Motor Vehicles: Excise Duties","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how much was generated from vehicle excise duty receipts in Greater Manchester in the last year for which information is available.","false","Biography information for Jim McMahon","Oldham West and Royton","Jim McMahon","42156"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533629","Department for Transport","false","2016-07-12","<p>My Rt Hon Friend the Secretary of State has met with the Secretaries of State for Work and Pensions and for Business, Innovation and Skills regarding HGV driver training and officials at the Departments for Transport, Work and Pensions and Business Innovation and Skills continue to work together to help the freight industry address the driver shortage.</p><p> </p><p>The supply of new drivers has been increasing with about 10,000 more HGV driving test passes in 2015/16 compared to two years before.</p><p> </p><p>The industry has recently launched its Trailblazer Apprenticeship which will be funded through the apprenticeship levy. The Government is working to provide support for groups of people who need it most – for example jobseekers, people facing redundancy and specialist career transitions such as those leaving Military service.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2016-07-12T10:20:58.813Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533629/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533629/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533629/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-07-07","Large Goods Vehicle Drivers: Training","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, pursuant to his Oral Answer of 30 June 2016 to Question 905567, HC Deb, column 463, what discussions he has had with the Secretaries of State for Work and Pensions and Business, Innovation and Skills on the provision of grants for HGV training; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Alan Brown","Kilmarnock and Loudoun","Alan Brown","42207"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533630","Department for Transport","false","2016-07-12","<p>Highways England’s systems are used to record incidents that occur on the Strategic Road Network.</p><p> </p><p>Between 1 January 2016 and 30 June 2016, the number of incidents defined as either suicide or attempted suicide was 568.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2016-07-12T10:59:14.42Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533630/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533630/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533630/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-07-07","Roads: Suicide","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, pursuant to the Answer of 25 February 2016 to Question 27762, on roads: suicide, how many suicides or attempted suicides have been recorded on the Strategic Road Network in 2016 up to the most recent period for which figures are available.","false","Biography information for Lilian Greenwood","Nottingham South","Lilian Greenwood","42206"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533631","Department for Transport","false","2016-07-12","<p>The Midland Main Line programme will deliver electrification of the Midland Main Line from Bedford to Kettering and Corby by 2019 and from Kettering to Nottingham and Sheffield via Derby by 2023. Following the vote taken by the British people for the UK to leave the European Union on 23 June their will must be respected and delivered. The Prime Minister has been clear that the negotiation for Britain's future relationship with Europe will need to begin under a new Prime Minister. In the meantime, the Department continues working to deliver the Government agenda, including the above electrification programme.</p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2016-07-12T10:51:03.063Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533631/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533631/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533631/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-07-07","Midland Main Railway Line: Electrification","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what assessment he has made of the potential effect of the UK leaving the EU on his Department's plans for electrification of the Midland Main Line.","false","Biography information for Lilian Greenwood","Nottingham South","Lilian Greenwood","42177"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533632","Department for Transport","false","2016-07-12","<p>Transport safety is a key objective of the Government and the UK has one of the safest railways in Europe. Each operator is responsible for the safety of their staff, passengers and services. The Office of Rail and Road’s duty is to ensure that those responsible for keeping Britain's railways safe for passengers, and providing a safe place for staff to work, do so.</p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2016-07-12T10:54:46.657Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533632/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533632/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533632/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-07-07","Govia Thameslink Railway: Safety","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what information his Department holds on which safety responsibilities Govia Thameslink Railway Ltd plans to be discharged by staff employed in the proposed role of on-board supervisor.","false","Biography information for Lilian Greenwood","Nottingham South","Lilian Greenwood","42178"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533633","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-07-12","<p>The Government is committed to eliminating child poverty and improving life chances for children.</p><p> </p><p>We know that work is the best route out of poverty, and Universal Credit is designed to strengthen incentives for parents to move into and progress in work. Evidence shows claimants move into work significantly faster and earn more than under the current system.</p><p> </p><p>In addition, Universal Credit now provides for 85% of childcare costs meaning more support for hardworking families.</p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson",,"2016-07-12T14:06:15.707Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533633/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533633/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533633/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-07-07","Universal Credit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many children he expects will be lifted out of poverty by the introduction of universal credit.","false","Biography information for Frank Field","Birkenhead","Frank Field","42172"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533634","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-07-12","<p>The Department’s timetable for the closure of Child Support Agency arrears only cases is currently under consideration.</p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson",,"2016-07-12T14:43:39.837Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533634/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533634/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533634/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-07-07","Children: Maintenance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, with reference to the Answer of 1 December 2015 to Question 17582, what his Department's timetable is for the closure of the remaining arrears-only Child Support Agency cases after the three-year cases closure programme involving cases with an on-going liability is completed.","false","Biography information for Steve McCabe","Birmingham, Selly Oak","Steve McCabe","42169"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533635","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-07-12","<p>The Department is in the process of reviewing all of its estates requirements as the current contract for most of the estate comes to an end on 31 March 2018. No decision has been made on the future of Oldham Jobcentre Plus by the Department.</p><p>Commercial negotiations are underway on the entirety of our estate at this time and it is not appropriate to comment further on individual sites while negotiations are in progress.</p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson",,"2016-07-12T13:56:49.947Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533635/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533635/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533635/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-07-07","Jobcentres: Oldham","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, whether his Department plans to (a) close or (b) change the functions of the Jobcentre Plus facility in Oldham town centre.","false","Biography information for Jim McMahon","Oldham West and Royton","Jim McMahon","42154"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533636","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-07-15","<p>In March 2016 approximately 6,600 Employment and Support Allowance claimants with a long-term and degenerative condition as their primary condition also received Personal Independence Payment.</p><p>‘Long-term and degenerative conditions’ include cystic fibrosis, multiple sclerosis, other rheumatoid arthritis, Parkinson’s disease and spinal muscular atrophy.</p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson",,"2016-07-15T13:14:17.663Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533636/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533636/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533636/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-07-07","Social Security Benefits: Disability","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many people are concurrently claiming employment and support allowance and personal independence payments for long-term and degenerative conditions.","false","Biography information for Stephen Kinnock","Aberavon","Stephen Kinnock","42125"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533637","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-07-13","<p>Departmental analysts forecast projected volumes of Personal Independence Payment Mandatory Reconsiderations and appeals; these projections are used to determine staffing requirements. The assessment of the Department’s capacity to handle volumes is determined from current deployment, planned recruitment and attrition rates. The information is updated, reported and reviewed on a monthly basis.</p><p> </p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson",,"2016-07-13T14:01:06.93Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533637/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533637/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533637/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-07-07","Personal Independence Payment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what assessment he has made of his Department's capacity to manage the appeals and review process for personal independence payments.","false","Biography information for Stephen Kinnock","Aberavon","Stephen Kinnock","42126"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533638","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-07-13","<p>No specific such assessment was carried out.</p><p> </p><p>Citizens Advice Bureaux have been, and continue to be, members of the Personal Independence Payment Implementation Stakeholder Forum and regularly engage with the Department on PIP issues.</p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson",,"2016-07-13T12:17:43.157Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533638/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533638/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533638/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-07-07","Personal Independence Payment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, whether his Department carried out an assessment prior to the introduction of personal independence payments for existing disability living allowance recipients of the effect of that introduction on advice services such as Citizens Advice Bureaux.","false","Biography information for Stephen Kinnock","Aberavon","Stephen Kinnock","42127"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533640","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-07-14","<p>Area reviews are about ensuring post 16 institutions are in the best state possible to meet the economic and educational needs of their areas and financially resilient for the long term. Colleges will be able to invest any savings created through implementation of area review recommendations in improved front line services, including better delivery of apprenticeships and higher level skills. This is expected to be the position in Greater Manchester, which is due to conclude shortly.</p>","Grantham and Stamford","Nick Boles",,"2016-07-14T10:05:47.253Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533640/answer","Biography information for Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533640/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533640/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-07-07","Further Education: Greater Manchester","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what savings to the public purse he expects to be made as a result of the post-16 education and training area review in Greater Manchester.","false","Biography information for Jim McMahon","Oldham West and Royton","Jim McMahon","42192"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533641","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-07-20","<p>As my right hon. Friend the Prime Minister has made clear, while the UK remains a member of the EU, current EU funding and collaboration arrangements continue unchanged, including those that apply to students, researchers, and businesses. I am in close contact with Commissioner Moedas on the topic of Horizon 2020 funding, and I met with the Italian Minister for Education, Universities and Research on 11 July.</p><p>The UK is world-class in research and innovation and we play a leading role in major European and international collaboration, including ESA and CERN.</p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson","42184 ; 42196","2016-07-20T14:47:38.727Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533641/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533641/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533641/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-07-07","Research: EU Grants and Loans","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what representations the Minister of State for Universities and Science has made to his European counterparts since the EU referendum on access to EU research grants for UK researchers.","false","Biography information for Daniel Zeichner","Cambridge","Daniel Zeichner","42202"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533642","HM Treasury","false","2016-07-14","<p>Horizon 2020 is the main EU Research and Innovation programme. The European Commission made the following statement on 4 July 2016:</p><p> </p><p>“The Statement of 29 June of the Heads of State or Government of 27 Member States, as well as the Presidents of the European Council and the European Commission, confirms that until the UK leaves the EU, EU law continues to apply to and within the UK, both when it comes to rights and obligations. This includes the eligibility of UK legal entities to participate and receive funding in Horizon 2020 actions.”</p><p> </p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2016-07-14T09:18:01.557Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533642/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533642/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533642/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-07-07","Science: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, if he will make it his policy to replace any reductions in private investment and access to EU research grants occurring as a result of the vote to leave the EU by increasing the science budget.","false","Biography information for Daniel Zeichner","Cambridge","Daniel Zeichner","42201"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533643","Church Commissioners","false","2016-07-12","<p>The Child Friendly Church Award, now achieved by well over 100 churches in the Diocese of Blackburn, places children at the centre of the worship &amp; ministry of our parish churches. This ensures that mothers who wish to breastfeed will find a warm welcome and adequate provision in these churches. We are grateful to the honourable member for the interest he continues to take in the detailed domestic affairs of the parishes of the diocese. I would encourage him to take this up with the Bishop in his own diocese with regard to making progress at a local level.</p><p> </p>","Meriden","Mrs Caroline Spelman",,"2016-07-12T16:10:34.17Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533643/answer","Biography information for Dame Caroline Spelman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533643/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533643/answer",,,,,"9","Church Commissioners","Church Commissioners","2016-07-07","Churches: Blackburn","1","House of Commons","To ask the right hon. Member for Meriden, representing the Church Commissioners, what facilities are available for (a) lactating mothers and (b) the changing of babies within churches in the Diocese of Blackburn (i) during church services and (ii) at other times.","false","Biography information for Sir Mark Hendrick","Preston","Mr Mark Hendrick","42226"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533644","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-07-13","<p>Since the announcement of the multi-year settlement offer in December 2015 we have recorded interest from over 125 councils.</p><p>Councils have until 14 October 2016 to apply to accept the offer of a multi-year settlement and submit their efficiency plan.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2016-07-13T14:27:00.107Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533644/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533644/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533644/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-07-07","Local Government Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, how many local authorities to date have submitted efficiency plans in order to qualify for a multi-year financial settlement.","false","Biography information for Jim McMahon","Oldham West and Royton","Jim McMahon","42193"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533645","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-07-13","<p>The Government is committed to protecting the most vulnerable, including through protecting and further boosting the supported housing supply we have already.</p><p>We are continuing to work with the supported housing sector and other partners to develop a sustainable and workable future for supported housing and will announce next steps in due course.</p><p>In the meantime we have put in place a one year exemption for supported housing from the Local Housing Allowance cap.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2016-07-13T14:29:02.983Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533645/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533645/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533645/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-07-07","Housing: Construction","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what assessment he has made of the effect of the local housing allowance cap on the capacity of housing providers to build new homes.","false","Biography information for Neil Coyle","Bermondsey and Old Southwark","Neil Coyle","42200"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533646","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-07-12","<p>Recommendation 17 of the International Olympic Committee's Agenda 2020 seeks to honour clean athletes by awarding an Olympic medal following a positive doping case. This involves organising formal medal ceremonies for medal-winners who receive their Olympic medal following the disqualification of a competitor.</p><p><br>Last month Australian athlete Jared Tallent was presented with an Olympic gold medal for the 50km walk at the London 2012 Games following the disqualification of a Russian athlete for a doping offence. We expect the same treatment for British athletes.</p>","Chatham and Aylesford","Tracey Crouch",,"2016-07-12T14:22:35.673Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533646/answer","Biography information for Tracey Crouch","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533646/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533646/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-07-07","Sports: Drugs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, if he will make representations to the International Olympic Committee on upgrading the medals of British athletes who were placed behind athletes found guilty of doping in competitions.","false","Biography information for Marion Fellows","Motherwell and Wishaw","Marion Fellows","42237"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533647","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-07-12","<p>As previously stated in the House of Commons, Government is reviewing the situation and I hope to announce details of a review in due course.</p>","Chatham and Aylesford","Tracey Crouch","42221 ; 42222","2016-07-12T15:46:44.297Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533647/answer","Biography information for Tracey Crouch","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533647/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533647/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-07-07","Gaming Machines","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what progress his Department has made on the Triennial Review of gaming machine stakes and prizes.","false","Biography information for Carolyn Harris","Swansea East","Carolyn Harris","42220"
