"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533296","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-07-13","<p>The Higher Education and Research Bill provides for a power to authorise Degree Awarding Powers on a time-limited basis. We intend this to be the vehicle to implement the concept of probationary Degree Awarding Powers, which was set out in our White Paper ‘Success As A Knowledge Economy’.</p><p> </p><p>Subject to the passage of the Bill, we plan to consult on the detail of the proposed changes to the Degree Awarding Powers, leading to new criteria and guidance. This would include the requirements and processes that will apply to providers seeking probationary taught or foundation Degree Awarding Powers. As now, we intend that details of all providers who have obtained Degree Awarding Powers will be publicly available. We envisage that this would indicate which providers have obtained those powers on a probationary basis.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2016-07-13T14:30:52.89Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533296/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533296/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533296/answer","Orpington","Joseph Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/533296/answer/previousversion/6538","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-07-06","Higher Education","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, when he plans to publish information on high quality higher education providers obtaining foundation or taught degree awarding powers on a probationary three year time-limited basis.","false","Biography information for Paul Blomfield","Sheffield Central","Paul Blomfield","42021"
